# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: esther-lederberg
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:esther-lederberg/alexander-hollaender] Hollaender was born in Samter, German Empire (Szamotuły, Poland), he emigrated to the US in 1921.
[src:esther-lederberg/alexander-hollaender] In 1939 Hollaender published research showing that the mutations of spores of the ringworm fungus occurred in the same spectrum as the absorption spectrum of nucleic acids indicating that nucleic acids form the building blocks of genes.
[src:esther-lederberg/alexander-hollaender] Public Health Service (Bethesda, MD), published with Dr.
[src:esther-lederberg/alexander-hollaender] Hollaender, Eva Sansome and Milislav Demerec in this very early field of x-ray- and UV-induced mutations.
[src:esther-lederberg/alexander-hollaender] In later years, Esther Zimmer (subsequentlyEsther Lederberg) became one of the most influential founders of bacterial and bacteriophage (Lambda phage) genetics.
[src:esther-lederberg/alexander-hollaender] From 1946 to 1966 Hollaender was the director of the Biology Division at Oak Ridge National Laboratories, where he worked with M.
[src:esther-lederberg/alexander-hollaender] Laurance Morse, who himself was a collaborator with Esther Lederberg.
[src:esther-lederberg/alexander-hollaender] His research was not appreciated for its discovery at the time, and later scientists reports were necessary before science accepted the role of nucleic acids as the genetic material.
[src:esther-lederberg/alexander-hollaender] Historians of science now realize his early discovery, and his Fermi Award recognized this discovery.
[src:esther-lederberg/alexander-hollaender] In 1981 Hollaender established the Council for Research Planning in Biological Sciences, and was its president at the time of his death from a pulmonary embolism in 1986.
[src:esther-lederberg/alexander-hollaender] The US National Academy of Sciences gives the Alexander Hollaender Award in Biophysics every three years in his honor.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p01] Antibiotic resistance is a serious result of AMR.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p01] Resistance arises through spontaneous mutation, horizontal gene transfer, and increased selective pressure from antibiotic overuse, both in medicine and agriculture, which accelerates resistance development.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p01] Preventive measures, such as using narrow-spectrum antibiotics and improving hygiene practices, aim to reduce the spread of resistance.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p01] The World Health Organization (WHO) claims that AMR is one of the top global public health and development threats, estimating that bacterial AMR was directly responsible for 1.27 million global deaths in 2019 and contributed to 4.95 million deaths.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p01] The burden of AMR is immense, with nearly 5 million annual deaths associated with resistant infections.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p01] Infections from AMR microbes are more challenging to treat and often require costly alternative therapies that may have more severe side effects.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p01] Moreover, the WHO and other international bodies warn that AMR could lead to up to 10 million deaths annually by 2050 unless actions are taken.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p01] Global initiatives, such as calls for international AMR treaties, emphasize coordinated efforts to limit misuse, fund research, and provide access to necessary antimicrobials in developing nations.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p01] However, the COVID-19 pandemic redirected resources and scientific attention away from AMR, intensifying the challenge.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p01] Antimicrobial resistance means that a microorganism is resistant to an antimicrobial drug that was once able to treat an infection by that microorganism.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p01] Resistance is a property of the microbe, not a person or other organism infected by a microbe.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p01] All types of microbes can develop drug resistance.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p01] Thus, there are antibiotic, antifungal, antiviral and antiparasitic resistance.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p01] Antibiotic resistance is a subset of antimicrobial resistance.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p01] This more specific resistance is linked to bacteria and thus broken down into two further subsets, microbiological and clinical.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p01] Microbiological resistance is the most common and occurs from genes, mutated or inherited, that allow the bacteria to resist the mechanism to kill the microbe associated with certain antibiotics.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p01] Clinical resistance is shown through the failure of many therapeutic techniques where the bacteria that are normally susceptible to a treatment become resistant after surviving the outcome of the treatment.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p01] In both cases of acquired resistance, the bacteria can pass the genetic catalyst for resistance through horizontal gene transfer: conjugation, transduction, or transformation.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p01] This allows the resistance to spread across the same species of pathogen or even similar bacterial pathogens.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p01] WHO report released April 2014 stated, "this serious threat is no longer a prediction for the future, it is happening right now in every region of the world and has the potential to affect anyone, of any age, in any country.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p01] In 2024, nearly 5 million deaths were associated with AMR and deaths attributable to AMR numbered 1.27 million.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p01] One in five people who died due to AMR were children under five years old.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p01] In 2018, WHO considered antibiotic resistance to be one of the biggest threats to global health, food security and development.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p01] The European Centre for Disease Prevention and Control calculated that in 2015 there were 671,689 infections in the EU and European Economic Area caused by antibiotic-resistant bacteria, resulting in 33,110 deaths.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p01] Most were acquired in healthcare settings.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p01] In 2019 there were 133,000 deaths caused by AMR.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p01] AMR is driven largely by the misuse and overuse of antimicrobials.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p01] They reproduce and spread quickly, and they also can adapt to their environment and change how well they can survive.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p01] Yet, at the same time, many people do not have access to essential antimicrobials.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p01] This leads to microbes either evolving a defense against drugs used to treat them, or certain strains of microbes that have a natural resistance to antimicrobials becoming much more prevalent than the ones that are easily defeated with medication.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p01] Genetic changes can also occur, which would allow the microbe to survive.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p01] While antimicrobial resistance does occur naturally over time, the use of antimicrobial agents in a variety of settings both within the healthcare industry and outside of has led to antimicrobial resistance becoming increasingly more prevalent.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p01] Although many microbes develop resistance to antibiotics over time through natural mutation, overprescribing and inappropriate prescription of antibiotics have accelerated the problem.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p01] During mutation, when replication happens, these mutations help individual microbes survive exposure.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p01] (NIAID, 2025) It is possible that as many as 1 in 3 prescriptions written for antibiotics are unnecessary.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p01] Every year, approximately 154 million prescriptions for antibiotics are written.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p01] Of these, up to 46 million are unnecessary or inappropriate for the condition that the patient has.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p01] Microbes may naturally develop resistance through genetic mutations that occur during cell division, and although random mutations are rare, many microbes reproduce frequently and rapidly, increasing the chances of members of the population acquiring a mutation that increases resistance.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p01] In contrast to that, recent research suggests that, contrary to the traditional model of rapid genetic mutation, mycobacteria maintain high genomic stability under antibiotic pressure, relying instead on phenotypic tolerance and DNA-repair mechanisms for survival.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p01] Many individuals stop taking antibiotics when they begin to feel better.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p01] When this occurs, it is possible that the microbes that are less susceptible to treatment still remain in the body.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p01] If these microbes are able to continue to reproduce, this can lead to an infection by bacteria that are less susceptible or even resistant to an antibiotic.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p01] Microbes may also get genes from each other, which makes them drug-resistant.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p01] Bacteria that have drug-resistant DNA often transfer a copy of these genes to the other bacteria.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p01] This process, known as horizontal gene transfer, allows resistance genes to spread rapidly between different bacterial species through mechanisms such as conjugation, transformation, and transduction.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p01] Bacteria become resistant to antibiotics by changing themselves or acquiring resistance genes from other bacteria.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p01] Over the past 20 years, antimicrobial resistance (AMR) has grown, making common infections like respiratory infections, urinary tract infections, STDs, and tuberculosis harder to treat.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p01] New antibiotics are not being developed fast enough and may lead to a "post-antibiotic era" where some infections are untreatable.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p01] AMR makes infections more difficult and costly to treat.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p01] Proper antibiotic use—correct drug, dose, and duration—and strict hospital hygiene are essential.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p01] Combating AMR requires cooperation among governments, healthcare workers, researchers, pharmaceutical companies, farmers, and the public through responsible antibiotic use, monitoring resistance, limiting antibiotics in animals, and improving access to medicines, vaccines, and tests.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p01] Prevention is the most effective strategy.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p01] Along with careful antibiotic use, there is a need for new drugs, alternative treatments, better diagnostics, and vaccines.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p01] Without coordinated global action, vital medical procedures like surgery, organ transplants, neonatal care, and cancer treatment could be at risk.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p01] Antimicrobial resistance can evolve naturally due to continued exposure to antimicrobials.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p01] Natural selection means that organisms that are able to adapt to their environment, survive, and continue to produce offspring.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p01] As a result, the types of microorganisms that are able to survive over time with continued attack by certain antimicrobial agents will naturally become more prevalent in the environment, and those without this resistance will become obsolete.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p01] Some contemporary antimicrobial resistances have also evolved naturally before the use of antimicrobials of human clinical uses.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p01] For instance, methicillin-resistance evolved as a pathogen of hedgehogs, possibly as a co-evolutionary adaptation of the pathogen to hedgehogs that are infected by a dermatophyte that naturally produces antibiotics.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p01] Also, many soil fungi and bacteria are natural competitors and the original antibiotic penicillin discovered by Alexander Fleming rapidly lost clinical effectiveness in treating humans and, furthermore, none of the other natural penicillins (F, K, N, X, O, U1 or U6) are currently in clinical use.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p01] Antimicrobial resistance can be acquired from other microbes through swapping genes in a process termed horizontal gene transfer.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p01] This means that once a gene for resistance to an antibiotic appears in a microbial community, it can then spread to other microbes, potentially moving from a non-disease causing microbe to a disease-causing microbe.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p01] This process is heavily driven by the natural selection processes that happen during antibiotic use or misuse.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p01] Over time, most of the strains of bacteria and infections present will be the type resistant to the antimicrobial agent being used to treat them, making this agent now ineffective to defeat most microbes.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p01] With the increased use of antimicrobial agents, there is a speeding up of this natural process.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p01] In the vast majority of countries, antibiotics can only be prescribed by a doctor and supplied by a pharmacy.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p01] Self-medication by consumers is defined as "the taking of medicines on one's own initiative or on another person's suggestion, who is not a certified medical professional", and it has been identified as one of the primary reasons for the evolution of antimicrobial resistance.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p01] Self-medication with antibiotics is an unsuitable way of using them but a common practice in resource-constrained countries.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p01] The practice exposes individuals to the risk of bacteria that have developed antimicrobial resistance.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p01] Many people resort to this out of necessity, when access to a physician is unavailable, or when patients have a limited amount of time or money to see a doctor.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p01] This increased access makes it extremely easy to obtain antimicrobials.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p01] An example is India, where in the state of Punjab 73% of the population resorted to treating their minor health issues and chronic illnesses through self-medication.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p01] Self-medication is higher outside the hospital environment.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p01] The prevalence of self-medication in low- and middle-income countries (LMICs) ranges from 8.1% to 93%.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p01] Accessibility, affordability, and conditions of health facilities, as well as the health-seeking behavior, are factors that influence self-medication in low- and middle-income countries.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p01] To determine the public's knowledge and preconceived notions on antibiotic resistance, a screening of 3,537 articles published in Europe, Asia, and North America was done.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p01] Of the 55,225 total people surveyed in the articles, 70% had heard of antibiotic resistance previously, but 88% of those people thought it referred to some type of physical change in the human body.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p01] Clinical misuse by healthcare professionals is another contributor to increased antimicrobial resistance.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p01] Studies done in the US show that the indication for treatment of antibiotics, choice of the agent used, and the duration of therapy was incorrect in up to 50% of the cases studied.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p01] In 2010 and 2011 about a third of antibiotic prescriptions in outpatient settings in the United States were not necessary.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p01] Another study in an intensive care unit in a major hospital in France has shown that 30% to 60% of prescribed antibiotics were unnecessary.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p01] These inappropriate uses of antimicrobial agents promote the evolution of antimicrobial resistance by supporting the bacteria in developing genetic alterations that lead to resistance.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p01] This demonstrates that many doctors underestimate the impact that their own prescribing habits have on antimicrobial resistance as a whole.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p01] It also confirms that some physicians may be overly cautious and prescribe antibiotics for both medical or legal reasons, even when clinical indications for use of these medications are not always confirmed.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p01] This can lead to unnecessary antimicrobial use, a pattern which may have worsened during the COVID-19 pandemic.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p01] Studies have shown that common misconceptions about the effectiveness and necessity of antibiotics to treat common mild illnesses contribute to their overuse.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p01] Important to the conversation of antibiotic use is the veterinary medical system.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p01] Veterinary oversight is required by law for all medically important antibiotics.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p01] Veterinarians use the Pharmacokinetic/pharmacodynamic model (PK/PD) approach to ensuring that the correct dose of the drug is delivered to the correct place at the correct timing.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p01] Increased antibiotic use during the early waves of the COVID-19 pandemic may exacerbate this global health challenge.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p01] Moreover, pandemic burdens on some healthcare systems may contribute to antibiotic-resistant infections.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p01] The use of disinfectants such as alcohol-based hand sanitizers, and antiseptic hand wash may also have the potential to increase antimicrobial resistance.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p01] Overuse of disinfectants can lead to mutations that induce antimicrobial resistance.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p01] On the other hand, "increased hand hygiene, decreased international travel, and decreased elective hospital procedures may have reduced AMR pathogen selection and spread in the short term" during the COVID-19 pandemic.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p01] Critically ill patients are prone to infections, and because of that, they often require antimicrobials.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p01] The more antimicrobials, the more resistance one becomes to it.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p01] Antimicrobial resistance (AMR) significantly strains healthcare systems and national economies.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p01] The World Bank estimates that by 2050, AMR could increase healthcare costs by around US$1 trillion and cause global economic losses of US$1–3.4 trillion annually by 2030.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p01] Resistant infections are harder to treat, often requiring longer hospital stays, additional tests, and stronger, more expensive medications, placing extra pressure on hospitals and health systems, especially during pandemics.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p01] A 2024 United Nations High-Level Meeting on AMR has pledged to reduce deaths associated with bacterial AMR by 10% over the next six years.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p01] In their first major declaration on the issue since 2016, global leaders also committed to raising $100 million to update and implement AMR action plans.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p01] However, the final draft of the declaration omitted an earlier target to reduce antibiotic use in animals by 30% by 2030, due to opposition from meat-producing countries and the farming industry.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p01] Critics argue this omission is a major weakness, as livestock accounts for around 73% of global sales of antimicrobial agents, including antibiotics, antivirals, and antiparasitics.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p01] Considering the complex interactions between humans, animals and the environment, it is also important to consider the environmental aspects and contributors to antimicrobial resistance.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p01] One of these factors is human and hospital waste, which is a substantial contributor to environmental antimicrobial resistance (AMR).
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p01] It is estimated that around 50–80% of antibiotics are passed unmetabolized in urine and 4–30% in feces, causing large quantities of active antibiotics to enter sewage systems.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p01] Sewage environments contain high levels of antimicrobial-resistant bacteria (ARB), antimicrobial resistance genes (ARGs), and mobile genetic elements such as plasmids, which enable rapid gene exchange.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p01] Wastewater treatment plants (WWTPs) are typically not designed to remove AMR; in some cases, multidrug-resistant species such as *Escherichia, Shigella, and Klebsiella* can increase twofold in treated wastewater.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p01] Methicillin-resistant *Staphylococcus aureus* (MRSA) has also been detected in both raw and treated sewage.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p01] Agriculture is also a major contributor to environmental AMR.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p01] Manure from livestock (such as cattle, sheep, etc.) contains residual antibiotics, which enter the soil as farmers usually use it as fertilizer.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p01] These are typically at levels of 1–10 mg/kg, and also contain ARBs and ARGs.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p01] One megaton of antibiotics has been estimated to have entered global soils through manure application.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p01] Pathogens can survive in soil for up to 10 years and on plant surfaces for up to 1 year, thereby enabling long-term environmental continuation of AMR.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p01] Because manure can be applied to diverse crops, residual antibiotics and resistance genes can enter plant tissues and the surrounding soil microbiota, contributing to AMR detected on fruits and vegetables.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p01] Heavy metals in soil, often introduced through fertilizers or industrial processes, can drive cross- and co-resistance mechanisms that select for antibiotic-resistant bacteria even when no antibiotics are present.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p01] Similar selective results happen with biocides and pesticides.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p01] Aquaculture is an underrecognized source of environmental AMR.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p01] Approximately 70% of antibiotics administered in aquaculture enter surrounding waterways, and tetracycline-resistant genes have been found even in isolated environments such as Antarctica and the Arctic.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p01] Antibiotic usage varies substantially across countries, showing the major differences in regulatory oversight.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p01] High antibiotic use in many Asian aquaculture systems has added to the elevated levels of clinically important resistance genes in sediments and river systems.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p01] Recent research has shown that AMR also occurs through the air.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p01] Airborne resistance genes have been detected at high levels in major urban centers, and farms have been determined as hotspots for airborne AMR, with resistance markers detected in the air surrounding animal operations.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p01] The antimicrobial resistance crisis also extends to the food industry, specifically with food producing animals.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p01] With an ever-increasing human population, there is constant pressure to intensify productivity in many agricultural sectors, including the production of meat as a source of protein.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p01] Antibiotics are fed to livestock to act as growth supplements, and a preventive measure to decrease the likelihood of infections.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p01] Farmers typically use antibiotics in animal feed to improve growth rates and prevent infections.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p01] However, this is illogical as antibiotics are used to treat infections and not prevent infections.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p01] 80% of antibiotic use in the U.S. is for agricultural purposes and about 70% of these are medically important.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p01] Overusing antibiotics gives the bacteria time to adapt leaving higher doses or even stronger antibiotics needed to combat the infection.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p01] Though antibiotics for growth promotion were banned throughout the EU in 2006, 40 countries still use antibiotics to promote growth.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p01] This can result in the transfer of resistant bacterial strains into the food that humans eat, causing potentially fatal transfer of disease.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p01] While the practice of using antibiotics as growth promoters does result in better yields and meat products, it is a major issue and needs to be decreased to prevent antimicrobial resistance.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p01] Though the evidence linking antimicrobial usage in livestock to antimicrobial resistance is limited, the World Health Organization Advisory Group on Integrated Surveillance of Antimicrobial Resistance strongly recommended the reduction of use of medically important antimicrobials in livestock.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p01] Additionally, the Advisory Group stated that such antimicrobials should be expressly prohibited for both growth promotion and disease prevention in food producing animals.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p01] By mapping antimicrobial consumption in livestock, it was predicted that in 228 countries there would be a total 67% increase in consumption of antibiotics by livestock by 2030.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p01] In some countries such as Brazil, Russia, India, China, and South Africa it is predicted that a 99% increase will occur.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p01] Several countries have restricted the use of antibiotics in livestock, including Canada, China, Japan, and the US.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p01] These restrictions are sometimes associated with a reduction of the prevalence of antimicrobial resistance in humans.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p01] Most pesticides protect crops against insects and plants, but in some cases antimicrobial pesticides are used to protect against various microorganisms such as bacteria, viruses, fungi, algae, and protozoa.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p01] The overuse of many pesticides in an effort to have a higher yield of crops has resulted in many of these microbes evolving a tolerance against these antimicrobial agents.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p01] Currently there are over 4000 antimicrobial pesticides registered with the US Environmental Protection Agency (EPA) and sold to market, showing the widespread use of these agents.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p01] It is estimated that for every single meal a person consumes, 0.3 g of pesticides is used, as 90% of all pesticide use is in agriculture.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p01] A majority of these products are used to help defend against the spread of infectious diseases, and hopefully protect public health.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p01] But out of the large amount of pesticides used, it is also estimated that less than 0.1% of those antimicrobial agents, actually reach their targets.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p01] That leaves over 99% of all pesticides used available to contaminate other resources.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p01] In soil, air, and water these antimicrobial agents are able to spread, coming in contact with more microorganisms and leading to these microbes evolving mechanisms to tolerate and further resist pesticides.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p01] The use of antifungal azole pesticides that drive environmental azole resistance have been linked to azole resistance cases in the clinical setting.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p01] The same issues confront the novel antifungal classes (e.g. orotomides) which are again being used in both the clinic and agriculture.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p01] Wildlife, including wild and migratory birds, serve as indicators of ecosystem health.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p01] They act as a reservoir for zoonotic diseases and antimicrobial-resistant organisms.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p01] Birds are a key link between the transmission of zoonotic diseases to human populations.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p01] By the same token, increased contact between wild birds and human populations (including domesticated animals), has increased the amount of anti-microbial resistance (AMR) to the bird population.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p01] The introduction of AMR to wild birds positively correlates with human pollution and increased human contact.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p01] Additionally, wild birds can participate in horizontal gene transfer with bacteria, leading to the transmission of antibiotic-resistant genes (ARG).
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p01] For simplicity, wild bird populations can be divided into two major categories, wild sedentary birds and wild migrating birds.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p01] Wild sedentary bird exposure to AMR is through increased contact with densely populated areas, human waste, domestic animals, and domestic animal/livestock waste.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p01] Especially if they are predators, wild, sedentary birds can come into contact with prey that interact more closely with humans.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p01] Wild migrating birds interact with sedentary birds in different environments along their migration route.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p01] This increases the rate and diversity of AMR across varying ecosystems.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p01] Neglect of wildlife in the global discussions surrounding health security and AMR, creates large barriers to true AMR surveillance.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p01] The surveillance of antimicrobial-resistant resistant organisms in wild birds is a potential metric for the rate of AMR in the environment.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p01] This surveillance also allows for further investigation into the transmission routes between different ecosystems and human populations (including domesticated animals and livestock).
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p01] Such information gathered from wild bird biomes, can help identify patterns of diseased transmission and better target interventions.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p01] These targeted interventions can inform the use of antimicrobial agents and reduce the persistence of multidrug resistant organisms.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p01] Recent studies demonstrate the importance of wild birds as sentinels for AMR.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p01] For example, *Escherichia coli* isolated from free-ranging Bonelli's eagles (*Aquila fasciata*) in eastern Spain showed that 53.3% of isolates were resistant to at least one antimicrobial, and 29.3% were multidrug-resistant, despite the species' minimal exposure to human-associated environments.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p01] The study also reported resistance to colistin and meropenem, two last-resort antibiotics, and documented 19 different multidrug-resistance patterns, suggesting persistent and heterogeneous selective pressures in the environment.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p01] Because Bonelli's eagles live far from humans and urban areas, they acquire resistance largely through interactions with prey species that interact with humans.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p01] These findings demonstrate how AMR can spread into remote ecosystems via indirect pathways, strengthening the role of wild birds, particularly apex predators, as effective bioindicators in AMR surveillance.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p01] Permafrost is a term used to refer to any ground that remained frozen for two years or more, with the oldest known examples continuously frozen for around 700,000 years.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p01] In the recent decades, permafrost has been rapidly thawing due to climate change.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p01] The cold preserves any organic matter inside the permafrost, and it is possible for microorganisms to resume their life functions once it thaws.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p01] While some common pathogens such as influenza, smallpox or the bacteria associated with pneumonia have failed to survive intentional attempts to revive them, more cold-adapted microorganisms such as anthrax, or several ancient plant and amoeba viruses, have successfully survived prolonged thaw.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p01] Some scientists have argued that the inability of known causative agents of contagious diseases to survive being frozen and thawed makes this threat unlikely.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p01] Instead, there have been suggestions that when modern pathogenic bacteria interact with the ancient ones, they may, through horizontal gene transfer, pick up genetic sequences which are associated with antimicrobial resistance, exacerbating an already difficult issue.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p01] Antibiotics to which permafrost bacteria have displayed at least some resistance include chloramphenicol, streptomycin, kanamycin, gentamicin, tetracycline, spectinomycin and neomycin.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p01] However, other studies show that resistance levels in ancient bacteria to modern antibiotics remain lower than in the contemporary bacteria from the active layer of thawed ground above them, which may mean that this risk is "no greater" than from any other soil.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p01] There have been increasing public calls for global collective action to address the threat, including a proposal for an international treaty on antimicrobial resistance.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p01] Further detail and attention is still needed to recognize and measure trends in resistance on the international level; the idea of a global tracking system has been suggested but implementation has yet to occur.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p01] A system of this nature would provide insight to areas of high resistance as well as information necessary for evaluating programs, introducing interventions and other changes made to fight or reverse antibiotic resistance.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p02] Antimicrobial resistance (AMR) is commonly described within a *One Health* framework, which emphasizes the interconnected relationships between human health, animal health, and the environment.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p02] Antimicrobial use in clinical medicine, veterinary practice, and agriculture has been associated with the selection and spread of resistant microorganisms across these sectors.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p02] Research indicates that resistant bacteria and antimicrobial resistance genes can move between humans, animals, and environmental reservoirs through multiple pathways, including food production systems, direct contact, and exposure to contaminated water or soil.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p02] These pathways contribute to the persistence and wider dissemination of antimicrobial resistance beyond individual settings.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p02] Environmental sources have been increasingly examined in relation to AMR.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p02] Wastewater systems, agricultural runoff, and pharmaceutical residues have been identified as potential reservoirs where resistant microorganisms and resistance genes may persist.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p02] Such reservoirs may facilitate ongoing transmission between environmental, animal, and human populations.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p02] Efforts to address AMR within a One Health framework typically involve coordinated strategies across sectors, including antimicrobial stewardship, infection prevention and control, and improvements in sanitation and hygiene.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p02] Evidence from systematic reviews suggests that interventions such as farm biosecurity and water, sanitation, and hygiene (WASH) practices may reduce antimicrobial use and contribute to limiting the development and spread of resistance.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p02] Delaying or minimizing the use of antibiotics for certain conditions may help safely reduce their use.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p02] Antimicrobial treatment duration should be based on the infection and other health problems a person may have.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p02] For many infections once a person has improved there is little evidence that stopping treatment causes more resistance.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p02] Some, therefore, feel that stopping early may be reasonable in some cases.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p02] Other infections, however, do require long courses regardless of whether a person feels better.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p02] Delaying antibiotics for ailments such as a sore throat and otitis media may have no difference in the rate of complications compared with immediate antibiotics, for example.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p02] When treating respiratory tract infections, clinical judgement is required as to the appropriate treatment (delayed or immediate antibiotic use).
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p02] ResistanceOpen is an online global map of antimicrobial resistance developed by HealthMap which displays aggregated data on antimicrobial resistance from publicly available and user submitted data.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p02] The website can display data for a 25 miles (40 km) radius from a location.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p02] Users may submit data from antibiograms for individual hospitals or laboratories.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p02] European data is from the EARS-Net (European Antimicrobial Resistance Surveillance Network), part of the ECDC.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p02] ResistanceMap is a website by the Center for Disease Dynamics, Economics & Policy and provides data on antimicrobial resistance on a global level.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p02] The WHO's AMR global action plan also recommends antimicrobial resistance surveillance in animals.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p02] Initial steps in the EU for establishing the veterinary counterpart EARS-Vet (EARS-Net for veterinary medicine) have been made.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p02] AMR data from pets in particular is scarce, but needed to support antibiotic stewardship in veterinary medicine.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p02] By comparison there is a lack of national and international monitoring programs for antifungal resistance.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p02] Antimicrobial stewardship programmes appear useful in reducing rates of antimicrobial resistance.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p02] The antimicrobial stewardship program will also provide pharmacists with the knowledge to educate patients that antibiotics will not work for a virus for example.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p02] Excessive antimicrobial use has become one of the top contributors to the evolution of antimicrobial resistance.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p02] Since the beginning of the antimicrobial era, antimicrobials have been used to treat a wide range of infectious diseases.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p02] Overuse of antimicrobials has become the primary cause of rising levels of antimicrobial resistance.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p02] Prescribers are willing to prescribe antimicrobials to individuals who believe that antimicrobials can cure nearly all illnesses, including viral infections like the common cold.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p02] In an analysis of drug prescriptions, 36% of individuals with a cold or an upper respiratory infection (both usually viral in origin) were given prescriptions for antibiotics.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p02] These prescriptions increase the risk of further evolution of antibiotic resistant bacteria.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p02] Using antimicrobials without prescription is another driving force leading to the overuse of antibiotics to self-treat diseases like the common cold, cough, fever, and dysentery resulting in an epidemic of antibiotic resistance in countries like Bangladesh, risking its spread around the globe.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p02] Introducing strict antibiotic stewardship in the outpatient setting to reduce inappropriate prescribing of antibiotics may reduce the emerging bacterial resistance.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p02] The WHO AWaRe (Access, Watch, Reserve) guidance and antibiotic book has been introduced to guide antibiotic choice for the 30 most common infections in adults and children to reduce inappropriate prescribing in primary care and hospitals.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p02] Narrow-spectrum antibiotics are preferred due to their lower resistance potential, and broad-spectrum antibiotics are only recommended for people with more severe symptoms.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p02] Some antibiotics are more likely to confer resistance, so are kept as reserve antibiotics in the AWaRe book.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p02] Various diagnostic strategies have been employed to prevent the overuse of antifungal therapy in the clinic, proving a safe alternative to empirical antifungal therapy, and thus underpinning antifungal stewardship schemes.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p02] Antimicrobial stewardship teams in hospitals are encouraging optimal use of antimicrobials.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p02] The goals of antimicrobial stewardship are to help practitioners pick the right drug at the right dose and duration of therapy while preventing misuse and minimizing the development of resistance.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p02] Stewardship interventions may reduce the length of stay by an average of slightly over 1 day while not increasing the risk of death.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p02] Dispensing the exact number of antibiotic pharmaceutical units necessary to complete an ongoing treatment can reduce excess antibiotics.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p02] A 2025 cross-sectional study of 125 pharmacists at a UK NHS Foundation Trust examined knowledge, attitudes, and perceptions regarding antimicrobial stewardship following the COVID-19 pandemic.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p02] The study found that more than 85% of pharmacists recognized antimicrobial resistance as a public health concern.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p02] However, the pandemic created challenges, with 80% reporting that COVID-19 patient conditions influenced antibiotic prescription.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p02] A 2026 systematic review of 73 studies examined arthropod-mediated pathogen transmission in hospitals.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p02] Research indicates that cockroaches, flies, and ants frequently harbor multidrug-resistant bacteria, fungi, and viruses.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p02] While direct causality is difficult to prove, genetic evidence links these pests to hospital-associated infections.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p02] Given the volume of care provided in primary care (general practice), recent strategies have focused on reducing unnecessary antimicrobial prescribing in this setting.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p02] Simple interventions, such as written information explaining when taking antibiotics is not necessary, for example in common infections of the upper respiratory tract, have been shown to reduce antibiotic prescribing.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p02] Various tools are also available to help professionals decide if prescribing antimicrobials is necessary.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p02] Parental expectations, driven by the worry for their children's health, can influence how often children are prescribed antibiotics.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p02] Parents often rely on their clinician for advice and reassurance.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p02] However a lack of plain language information and not having adequate time for consultation negatively impacts this relationship.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p02] In effect parents often rely on past experiences in their expectations rather than reassurance from the clinician.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p02] Adequate time for consultation and plain language information can help parents make informed decisions and avoid unnecessary antibiotic use.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p02] The prescriber should closely adhere to the five rights of drug administration: the right patient, the right drug, the right dose, the right route, and the right time.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p02] Microbiological samples should be taken for culture and sensitivity testing before treatment when indicated and treatment potentially changed based on the susceptibility report.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p02] Health workers and pharmacists can help tackle antibiotic resistance by: enhancing infection prevention and control; only prescribing and dispensing antibiotics when they are truly needed; prescribing and dispensing the right antibiotic(s) to treat the illness.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p02] A unit dose system implemented in community pharmacies can also reduce antibiotic leftovers at households.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p02] Despite these, written guideline intervention for prescriber to do history taking and provision of advice and knowledge of pharmacists and non‐pharmacists may not reduce the sales of non‐prescription antimicrobial drugs in community pharmacies, drugstores, and other medicine outlets.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p02] People can help tackle resistance by using antibiotics only when prescribed for a bacterial infetion as well as completing the full treatment course, never sharing medication with others, and using proper disposal methods for excess drugs.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p02] Basic hygiene practices also help prevent the spread of bacteria.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p02] • Germany and Sweden also have lower prescribing rates, with Sweden's rate having been declining since 2007. • Greece, France and Belgium have high prescribing rates.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p02] Infectious disease control through improved water, sanitation and hygiene (WASH) infrastructure needs to be included in the antimicrobial resistance (AMR) agenda.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p02] Growing usage of antibiotics together with persistent infectious disease levels have led to a dangerous cycle in which reliance on antimicrobials increases while the efficacy of drugs diminishes.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p02] The proper use of infrastructure for water, sanitation and hygiene (WASH) can result in a 47–72 percent decrease of diarrhea cases treated with antibiotics depending on the type of intervention and its effectiveness.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p02] A reduction of the diarrhea disease burden through improved infrastructure would result in large decreases in the number of diarrhea cases treated with antibiotics.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p02] This was estimated as ranging from 5 million in Brazil to up to 590 million in India by the year 2030.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p02] The strong link between increased consumption and resistance indicates that this will directly mitigate the accelerating spread of AMR.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p02] Sanitation and water for all by 2030 is Goal Number 6 of the Sustainable Development Goals.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p02] An increase in hand washing compliance by hospital staff results in decreased rates of resistant organisms.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p02] Water supply and sanitation infrastructure in health facilities offer opportunities for combatting AMR, and investment should be increased.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p02] There is much room for improvement: WHO and UNICEF estimated in 2015 that 38% of health facilities did not have a source of water, nearly 19% had no toilets and 35% had no water and soap or alcohol-based hand rub for handwashing.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p02] Manufacturers of antimicrobials need to improve the treatment of their wastewater (by using industrial wastewater treatment processes) to reduce the release of residues into the environment.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p02] It is established that the use of antibiotics in animal husbandry can give rise to AMR resistances in bacteria found in food animals to the antibiotics being administered (through injections or medicated feeds).
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p02] For this reason only antimicrobials that are deemed "not-clinically relevant" are used in these practices.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p02] Unlike resistance to antibacterials, antifungal resistance can be driven by arable farming, currently there is no regulation on the use of similar antifungal classes in agriculture and the clinic.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p02] Recent studies have shown that the prophylactic use of "non-priority" or "non-clinically relevant" antimicrobials in feeds can potentially, under certain conditions, lead to co-selection of environmental AMR bacteria with resistance to medically important antibiotics.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p02] The possibility for co-selection of AMR resistances in the food chain pipeline may have far-reaching implications for human health.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p02] In 1997, European Union health ministers voted to ban avoparcin and four additional antibiotics used to promote animal growth in 1999.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p02] In 2006 a ban on the use of antibiotics in European feed, with the exception of two antibiotics in poultry feeds, became effective.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p02] In Scandinavia, there is evidence that the ban has led to a lower prevalence of antibiotic resistance in (nonhazardous) animal bacterial populations.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p02] As of 2004, several European countries established a decline of antimicrobial resistance in humans through limiting the use of antimicrobials in agriculture and food industries without jeopardizing animal health or economic cost.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p02] The United States Department of Agriculture (USDA) and the Food and Drug Administration (FDA) collect data on antibiotic use in humans and in a more limited fashion in animals.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p02] About 80% of antibiotic use in the U.S. is for agriculture purposes, and about 70% of these are medically important.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p02] This gives reason for concern about the antibiotic resistance crisis in the U.S. and more reason to monitor it.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p02] The FDA first determined in 1977 that there is evidence of emergence of antibiotic-resistant bacterial strains in livestock.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p02] The long-established practice of permitting OTC sales of antibiotics (including penicillin and other drugs) to lay animal owners for administration to their own animals nonetheless continued in all states.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p02] In 2000, the FDA announced their intention to revoke approval of fluoroquinolone use in poultry production because of substantial evidence linking it to the emergence of fluoroquinolone-resistant *Campylobacter* infections in humans.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p02] Legal challenges from the food animal and pharmaceutical industries delayed the final decision to do so until 2006.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p02] Fluroquinolones have been banned from extra-label use in food animals in the USA since 2007.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p02] However, they are still used in treatment of companion and exotic animals.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p02] The increasing interconnectedness of the world and the fact that new classes of antibiotics have not been developed and approved for 25 years highlight the extent to which antimicrobial resistance is a global health challenge.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p02] A global action plan to tackle the growing problem of resistance to antibiotics and other antimicrobial medicines was endorsed at the Sixty-eighth World Health Assembly in May 2015.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p02] One of the key objectives of the plan is to improve awareness and understanding of antimicrobial resistance through effective communication, education and training.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p02] This global action plan developed by the World Health Organization was created to combat the issue of antimicrobial resistance and was guided by the advice of countries and key stakeholders.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p02] The WHO's global action plan is composed of five key objectives that can be targeted through different means, and represents countries coming together to solve a major problem that can have future health consequences.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p02] The World Health Organization has promoted the first World Antibiotic Awareness Week running from 16 to 22 November 2015.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p02] The aim of the week is to increase global awareness of antibiotic resistance.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p02] It also wants to promote the correct usage of antibiotics across all fields to prevent further instances of antibiotic resistance.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p02] World Antibiotic Awareness Week has been held every November since 2015.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p02] For 2017, the Food and Agriculture Organization of the United Nations (FAO), the World Health Organization (WHO) and the World Organisation for Animal Health (OIE) are together calling for responsible use of antibiotics in humans and animals to reduce the emergence of antibiotic resistance.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p02] In 2016 the Secretary-General of the United Nations convened the Interagency Coordination Group (IACG) on Antimicrobial Resistance.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p02] The IACG worked with international organizations and experts in human, animal, and plant health to create a plan to fight antimicrobial resistance.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p02] Their report released in April 2019 focuses on the seriousness of antimicrobial resistance and the threat it poses to world health.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p02] It suggests five recommendations for member states to follow to tackle this increasing threat.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p02] The **One Health** approach recognizes that human, animal, and environmental health are interconnected in the development and spread of antimicrobial resistance (AMR).
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p02] Alteration of target- or binding site: for example, alteration of PBP—the binding target site of penicillins—in MRSA and other penicillin-resistant bacteria.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p02] Another protective mechanism found among bacterial species is ribosomal protection proteins.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p02] These proteins protect the bacterial cell from antibiotics that target the cell's ribosomes to inhibit protein synthesis.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p02] The mechanism involves the binding of the ribosomal protection proteins to the ribosomes of the bacterial cell, which in turn changes its conformational shape.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p02] This allows the ribosomes to continue synthesizing proteins essential to the cell while preventing antibiotics from binding to the ribosome to inhibit protein synthesis.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p02] Reduced drug accumulation: by decreasing drug permeability or increasing active efflux (pumping out) of the drugs across the cell surface.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p02] These multidrug efflux pumps within the cellular membrane of certain bacterial species are used to pump antibiotics out of the cell before they are able to do any damage.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p02] They are often activated by a specific substrate associated with an antibiotic, as in fluoroquinolone resistance.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p02] Ribosome splitting and recycling: for example, drug-mediated stalling of the ribosome by lincomycin and erythromycin unstalled by a heat shock protein found in *Listeria monocytogenes*, which is a homologue of HflX from other bacteria.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p02] Liberation of the ribosome from the drug allows further translation and consequent resistance to the drug.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p02] There are several different types of germs that have developed a resistance over time.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p02] The six pathogens causing most deaths associated with resistance are *Escherichia coli*, *Staphylococcus aureus, Klebsiella pneumoniae, Streptococcus pneumoniae, Acinetobacter baumannii*, and *Pseudomonas aeruginosa*.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p02] They were responsible for 929,000 deaths attributable to resistance and 3.57 million deaths associated with resistance in 2019.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p02] Penicillinase-producing *Neisseria gonorrhoeae* developed a resistance to penicillin in 1976.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p02] Another example is Azithromycin-resistant *Neisseria gonorrhoeae*, which developed a resistance to azithromycin in 2011.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p02] In gram-negative bacteria, plasmid-mediated resistance genes produce proteins that can bind to DNA gyrase, protecting it from the action of quinolones.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p02] Finally, mutations at key sites in DNA gyrase or topoisomerase IV can decrease their binding affinity to quinolones, decreasing the drug's effectiveness.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p02] Some bacteria are naturally resistant to certain antibiotics; for example, gram-negative bacteria are resistant to most β-lactam antibiotics due to the presence of β-lactamase.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p02] Antibiotic resistance can also be acquired as a result of either genetic mutation or horizontal gene transfer.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p02] Although mutations are rare, with spontaneous mutations in the pathogen genome occurring at a rate of about 1 in 105 to 1 in 108 per chromosomal replication, Bacteria reproduce at a high rate, lifespans and production of new generations can be on a timescale of mere hours.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p02] A new (de novo) mutation in a parent cell can quickly become an inherited mutation of widespread prevalence, resulting in the microevolution of a fully resistant colony.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p02] However, chromosomal mutations also confer a cost of fitness.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p02] For example, a ribosomal mutation may protect a bacterial cell by changing the binding site of an antibiotic but may result in slower growth rate.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p02] Moreover, some adaptive mutations can propagate not only through inheritance but also through horizontal gene transfer.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p02] The most common mechanism of horizontal gene transfer is the transferring of plasmids carrying antibiotic resistance genes between bacteria of the same or different species via conjugation.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p02] Recent findings show no necessity of large populations of bacteria for the appearance of antibiotic resistance.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p02] Small populations of *Escherichia coli* in an antibiotic gradient can become resistant.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p02] Any heterogeneous environment with respect to nutrient and antibiotic gradients may facilitate antibiotic resistance in small bacterial populations.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p02] Researchers hypothesize that the mechanism of resistance evolution is based on four SNP mutations in the genome of *E. coli* produced by the gradient of antibiotic.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p02] In one study, which has implications for space microbiology, a non-pathogenic strain *E. coli* MG1655 was exposed to trace levels of the broad spectrum antibiotic chloramphenicol, under simulated microgravity (LSMMG, or Low Shear Modeled Microgravity) over 1000 generations.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p02] Thus, irrespective of where they are used, the use of an antibiotic would likely result in persistent resistance to that antibiotic, as well as cross-resistance to other antimicrobials.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p02] In recent years, the emergence and spread of β-lactamases called carbapenemases has become a major health crisis.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p02] One such carbapenemase is New Delhi metallo-beta-lactamase 1 (NDM-1), an enzyme that makes bacteria resistant to a broad range of beta-lactam antibiotics.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p02] The most common bacteria that make this enzyme are gram-negative such as *E. coli* and *Klebsiella pneumoniae*, but the gene for NDM-1 can spread from one strain of bacteria to another by horizontal gene transfer.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p02] Specific antiviral drugs are used to treat some viral infections.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p02] These drugs prevent viruses from reproducing by inhibiting essential stages of the virus's replication cycle in infected cells.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p02] Antivirals are used to treat HIV, hepatitis B, hepatitis C, influenza, herpes viruses including varicella zoster virus, cytomegalovirus and Epstein–Barr virus.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p02] With each virus, some strains have become resistant to the administered drugs.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p02] Antiviral drugs typically target key components of viral reproduction; for example, oseltamivir targets influenza neuraminidase,while guanosine analogs inhibit viral DNA polymerase.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p02] Resistance to antivirals is thus acquired through mutations in the genes that encode the protein targets of the drugs.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p02] Resistance to HIV antivirals is problematic, and even multi-drug resistant strains have evolved.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p02] One source of resistance is that many current HIV drugs, including NRTIs and NNRTIs, target reverse transcriptase; however, HIV-1 reverse transcriptase is highly error prone and thus mutations conferring resistance arise rapidly.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p02] Resistant strains of the HIV virus emerge rapidly if only one antiviral drug is used.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p02] Using three or more drugs together, termed combination therapy, has helped to control this problem, but new drugs are needed because of the continuing emergence of drug-resistant HIV strains.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p02] Infections by fungi are a cause of high morbidity and mortality in immunocompromised persons, such as those with HIV/AIDS, tuberculosis or receiving chemotherapy.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p02] The fungi *Candida*, *Cryptococcus neoformans* and *Aspergillus fumigatus* cause most of these infections and antifungal resistance occurs in all of them.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p02] Multidrug resistance in fungi is increasing because of the widespread use of antifungal drugs to treat infections in immunocompromised individuals and the use of some agricultural antifungals.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p02] Antifungal resistant disease is associated with increased mortality.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p02] Some fungi (for example, *Candida krusei* and fluconazole) exhibit intrinsic resistance to certain antifungal drugs or classes, whereas some species develop antifungal resistance to external pressures.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p02] Antifungal resistance is a One Health concern, driven by multiple extrinsic factors, including overuse of fungicides, clinical antifungals, environmental change and host factors.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p02] In the USA fluconazole-resistant Candida species and azole resistance in Aspergillus fumigatus have been highlighted as a growing threat.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p02] 20 species of *Candida* can cause candidiasis infection, the most common of which is *Candida albicans*.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p02] *Candida* yeasts normally inhabit the skin and mucous membranes without causing infection.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p02] However, overgrowth of *Candida* can lead to candidiasis.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p02] *Candida glabrata)* are becoming resistant to first-line and second-line antifungal agents such as echinocandins and azoles.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p02] The emergence of *Candida auris* as a potential human pathogen that sometimes exhibits multi-class antifungal drug resistance is concerning and has been associated with several outbreaks.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p02] The WHO has released a priority fungal pathogen list, including pathogens with antifungal resistance.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p02] The identification of antifungal resistance is undermined by limited classical diagnosis of infection, where a culture is lacking, preventing susceptibility testing.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p02] National and international surveillance schemes for fungal disease and antifungal resistance are limited, hampering the understanding of the disease burden and associated resistance.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p02] The application of molecular testing to identify genetic markers associating with resistance may improve the identification of antifungal resistance, but the diversity of mutations associated with resistance is increasing across the fungal species causing infection.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p02] In addition, a number of resistance mechanisms depend on up-regulation of selected genes (for instance reflux pumps) rather than defined mutations that are amenable to molecular detection.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p02] Due to the limited number of antifungals in clinical use and the increasing global incidence of antifungal resistance, using the existing antifungals in combination might be beneficial in some cases but further research is needed.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p02] Similarly, other approaches that might help to combat the emergence of antifungal resistance could rely on the development of host-directed therapies such as immunotherapy or vaccines.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p02] The protozoan parasites that cause the diseases malaria, trypanosomiasis, toxoplasmosis, cryptosporidiosis and leishmaniasis are important human pathogens.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p02] Malarial parasites that are resistant to the drugs that are currently available to infections are common and this has led to increased efforts to develop new drugs.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p02] Resistance to recently developed drugs such as artemisinin has also been reported.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p02] The problem of drug resistance in malaria has driven efforts to develop vaccines.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p02] Trypanosomes are parasitic protozoa that cause African trypanosomiasis and Chagas disease (American trypanosomiasis).
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p02] There are no vaccines to prevent these infections so drugs such as pentamidine and suramin, benznidazole and nifurtimox are used to treat infections.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p02] These drugs are effective but infections caused by resistant parasites have been reported.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p02] Leishmaniasis is caused by protozoa and is a public health problem in sub-tropical and tropical countries.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p02] Drug resistance has "become a major concern".
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p02] The preferred treatment for leishmaniasis regionally; liposomal amphotericin B is used in the Mediterranean basin and pentavalent antimonials are more commonly used in Africa, South America, Bangladesh, India, and Nepal.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p02] Resistance to antibiotics in *Leishmania* is a relatively recent phenomena.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p02] The first reported instance of resistance to antimonials was reported in India in the 1980s.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p02] In 2022, genomic epidemiologists reported results from a global survey of antimicrobial resistance via genomic wastewater-based epidemiology, finding large regional variations, providing maps, and suggesting resistance genes are also passed on between microbial species that are not closely related.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p02] The WHO provides the Global Antimicrobial Resistance and Use Surveillance System (GLASS) reports which summarize annual (e.g.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p02] 2020's) data on international AMR, also including an interactive dashboard.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p02] Public Health England reported that the total number of antibiotic resistant infections in England rose by 9% from 55,812 in 2017 to 60,788 in 2018, but antibiotic consumption had fallen by 9% from 20.0 to 18.2 defined daily doses per 1,000 inhabitants per day between 2014 and 2018.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p02] The Centers for Disease Control and Prevention reported that 2.8 million cases of antibiotic resistance have been reported.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p02] However, in 2019 overall deaths from antibiotic-resistant infections decreased by 18% and deaths in hospitals decreased by 30%.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p02] The COVID pandemic caused a reversal of much of the progress made on attenuating the effects of antibiotic resistance, resulting in more antibiotic use, more resistant infections, and less data on preventive action.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p02] Hospital-onset infections and deaths both increased by 15% in 2020, and significantly higher rates of infections were reported for 4 out of 6 types of healthcare associated infections.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p02] Owing to rampant misuse, over-prescription, and unregulated over-the-counter access to antibiotics, the growth of AMR superbugs has proliferated in India.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p02] Pharmacies surveyed by the Karnataka government revealed that 80% of drugs were being sold without a prescription.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p02] In 2019, India reported 300,000 deaths because of infections relating to AMR, India also reports the most number of tuberculosis cases resistant to antibiotics.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p02] The 1950s to 1970s represented the golden age of antibiotic discovery, where countless new classes of antibiotics were discovered to treat previously incurable diseases such as tuberculosis and syphilis.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p02] However, since that time the discovery of new classes of antibiotics has been almost nonexistent, and represents a situation that is especially problematic considering the resiliency of bacteria shown over time and the continued misuse and overuse of antibiotics in treatment.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p02] Already in 1940, in their letter to the editor of Nature journal, Abraham and Chain identified the enzyme penicillinase as responsible for the deactivation of penicillin in penicillin-resistant bacteria.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p02] This discovery was the first step in understanding the mechanisms of microbial resistance to β-lactam antibiotics.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p02] The phenomenon of antimicrobial resistance caused by overuse of antibiotics was predicted as early as 1945 by Alexander Fleming who said "The time may come when penicillin can be bought by anyone in the shops.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p02] Antimicrobial resistance can lead to epidemics of enormous proportions if preventive actions are not taken.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p02] In this day and age current antimicrobial resistance leads to longer hospital stays, higher medical costs, and increased mortality.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p02] Since the mid-1980s pharmaceutical companies have invested in medications for cancer or chronic disease that have greater potential to make money and have "de-emphasized or dropped development of antibiotics".
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p02] On 20 January 2016 at the World Economic Forum, "80 pharmaceutical and diagnostic companies" called for "transformational commercial models" at an international level to spur research and development on antibiotics and on the use of diagnostic tests.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p02] A number of countries are considering or implementing delinked payment models for new antimicrobials whereby payment is based on value rather than volume of drug sales.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p02] This offers the opportunity to pay for valuable new drugs even if they are reserved for use in relatively rare drug resistant infections.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p02] Some global health scholars have argued that a global, legal framework is needed to prevent and control antimicrobial resistance.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p02] For instance, binding global policies could be used to create antimicrobial use standards, regulate antibiotic marketing, and strengthen global surveillance systems.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p02] Ensuring compliance of involved parties is a challenge.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p02] For the United States 2016 budget, U.S. president Barack Obama proposed to nearly double the amount of federal funding to "combat and prevent" antibiotic resistance to $1.2 billion.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p02] Many international funding agencies like USAID, DFID, Sida and Gates Foundation have pledged money for developing strategies to counter antimicrobial resistance.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p02] On 27 March 2015, the White House released a plan to address the increasing need for agencies to combat the rise of antibiotic-resistant bacteria.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p02] The Task Force for Combating Antibiotic-Resistant Bacteria developed *The National Action Plan for Combating Antibiotic-Resistant Bacteria* with the intent of providing a roadmap to guide the US in the antibiotic resistance challenge and with hopes of saving many lives.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p02] This plan outlines steps taken by the Federal government over the next five years needed to prevent and contain outbreaks of antibiotic-resistant infections; maintain the efficacy of antibiotics already on the market; and to help to develop future diagnostics, antibiotics, and vaccines.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p02] The Action Plan was developed around five goals with focuses on strengthening health care, public health veterinary medicine, agriculture, food safety and research, and manufacturing.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p02] As of 2023, AMR remains a public health threat in the United States.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p02] According to the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention's 2023 Report on Antibiotic Resistance Threats, over 2.8 million antibiotic-resistant infections occur in the U.S. each year, leading to at least 35,000 deaths annually.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p02] Among the most concerning resistant pathogens are Carbapenem-resistant *Enterobacteriaceae* (CRE), Methicillin-resistant *Staphylococcus aureus* (MRSA), and *Clostridioides difficile* (C. diff), all of which continue to be responsible for severe healthcare-associated infections (HAIs).
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p02] The COVID-19 pandemic led to a disruption in healthcare, with an increase in the use of antibiotics during the treatment of viral infections.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p02] This rise in antibiotic prescribing, coupled with overwhelmed healthcare systems, contributed to a resurgence in AMR during the pandemic years.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p02] A 2021 CDC report identified a sharp increase in HAIs caused by resistant pathogens in COVID-19 patients, a trend that has persisted into 2023.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p02] Recent data suggest that although antibiotic use has decreased since the pandemic, some resistant pathogens remain prevalent in healthcare settings.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p02] The CDC has also expanded its Get Ahead of Sepsis campaign in 2023, focusing on raising awareness of AMR's role in sepsis and promoting the judicious use of antibiotics in both healthcare and community settings.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p02] This initiative has reached millions through social media, healthcare facilities, and public health outreach, aiming to educate the public on the importance of preventing infections and reducing antibiotic misuse.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p02] Trump, severe federal funding cuts in 2025 at the National Institutes of Health (NIH) and many other research entities in the United States are expected to impede progress in combating antimicrobial resistance.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p02] Public health experts believe these budget reductions will adversely affect the development of new antibiotics as well as advances in diagnostics and treatment strategies, thus undermining efforts currently underway to address AMR.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p02] The Infectious Diseases Society of America (IDSA) is but one organization that has expressed grave concern regarding the negative consequences of such extreme budget measures on antimicrobial stewardship, and, as a result, on global health security overall.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p02] According to World Health Organization, policymakers can help tackle resistance by strengthening resistance-tracking and laboratory capacity and by regulating and promoting the appropriate use of medicines.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p02] Policymakers and industry can help tackle resistance by: fostering research and development of new tools and promoting cooperation and information sharing among all stakeholders.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p02] The U.S. government continues to prioritize AMR mitigation through policy and legislation.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p02] In 2023, the National Action Plan for Combating Antibiotic-Resistant Bacteria (CARB) 2023-2028 was released, outlining strategic objectives for reducing antibiotic-resistant infections, advancing infection prevention, and accelerating research on new antibiotics.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p02] The plan also emphasizes the importance of improving antibiotic stewardship across healthcare, agriculture, and veterinary settings.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p02] Furthermore, the PASTEUR Act (Pioneering Antimicrobial Subscriptions to End Upsurging Resistance) has gained momentum in Congress.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p02] If passed, the bill would create a subscription-based payment model to incentivize the development of new antimicrobial drugs, while supporting antimicrobial stewardship programs to reduce the misuse of existing antibiotics.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p02] This legislation is considered a critical step toward addressing the economic barriers to developing new antimicrobials.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p02] Measuring the costs and benefits of strategies to combat AMR is difficult and policies may only have effects in the distant future.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p02] In other infectious diseases this problem has been addressed by using mathematical models.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p02] More research is needed to understand how AMR develops and spreads so that mathematical modelling can be used to anticipate the likely effects of different policies.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p03] Distinguishing infections requiring antibiotics from self-limiting ones is clinically challenging.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p03] To guide appropriate use of antibiotics and prevent the evolution and spread of antimicrobial resistance, diagnostic tests that provide clinicians with timely, actionable results are needed.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p03] Acute fever is a common reason for seeking medical care and a major cause of morbidity and mortality.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p03] Multiple studies have shown that the use of malaria rapid diagnostic tests without reliable tools to distinguish other fever causes has resulted in increased antibiotic use.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p03] Antimicrobial susceptibility testing (AST) can facilitate a precision medicine approach to treatment by helping clinicians to prescribe more effective and targeted antimicrobial therapy.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p03] At the same time with traditional phenotypic AST it can take 12 to 48 hours to obtain a result due to the time taken for organisms to grow on/in culture media.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p03] Rapid testing, possible from molecular diagnostics innovations, is defined as "being feasible within an 8-h working shift".
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p03] There are several commercial Food and Drug Administration-approved assays available which can detect AMR genes from a variety of specimen types.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p03] Progress has been slow due to a range of reasons including cost and regulation.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p03] Genotypic AMR characterisation methods are, however, being increasingly used in combination with machine learning algorithms in research to help better predict phenotypic AMR from organism genotype.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p03] Optical techniques such as phase contrast microscopy in combination with single-cell analysis are another powerful method to monitor bacterial growth.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p03] In 2017, scientists from Uppsala University in Sweden published a method that applies principles of microfluidics and cell tracking, to monitor bacterial response to antibiotics in less than 30 minutes overall manipulation time.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p03] This invention was awarded the 8M£ Longitude Prize on AMR in 2024.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p03] Recently, this platform has been advanced by coupling microfluidic chip with optical tweezing to isolate bacteria with altered phenotype directly from the analytical matrix.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p03] Rapid diagnostic methods have also been trialled as antimicrobial stewardship interventions to influence the healthcare drivers of AMR.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p03] Serum procalcitonin measurement has been shown to reduce mortality rate, antimicrobial consumption and antimicrobial-related side-effects in patients with respiratory infections, but impact on AMR has not yet been demonstrated.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p03] Similarly, point of care serum testing of the inflammatory biomarker C-reactive protein has been shown to influence antimicrobial prescribing rates in this patient cohort, but further research is required to demonstrate an effect on rates of AMR.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p03] Clinical investigation to rule out bacterial infections are often done for patients with pediatric acute respiratory infections.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p03] Currently it is unclear if rapid viral testing affects antibiotic use in children.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p03] Vaccines are an essential part of the response to reduce AMR as they prevent infections, reduce the use and overuse of antimicrobials, and slow the emergence and spread of drug-resistant pathogens.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p03] Microorganisms usually do not develop resistance to vaccines because vaccines reduce the spread of the infection and target the pathogen in multiple ways in the same host and possibly in different ways between different hosts.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p03] Furthermore, if the use of vaccines increases, there is evidence that antibiotic resistant strains of pathogens will decrease; the need for antibiotics will naturally decrease as vaccines prevent infection before it occurs.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p03] A 2024 report by WHO finds that vaccines against 24 pathogens could reduce the number of antibiotics needed by 22% or 2.5 billion DDD every year.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p03] If vaccines could be rolled out against all the evaluated pathogens, they could save a third of the hospital costs associated with AMR.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p03] Vaccinated people have fewer infections and are protected against potential complications from secondary infections that may need antimicrobial medicines or require admission to hospital.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p03] However, there are well documented cases of vaccine resistance, although these are usually much less of a problem than antimicrobial resistance.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p03] Antistaphylococcal vaccines have shown limited efficacy, because of immunological variation between *Staphylococcus* species, and the limited duration of effectiveness of the antibodies produced.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p03] Development and testing of more effective vaccines is underway.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p03] Two registrational trials have evaluated vaccine candidates in active immunization strategies against *S. aureus* infection.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p03] In a phase II trial, a bivalent vaccine of capsular proteins 5 & 8 was tested in 1804 hemodialysis patients with a primary fistula or synthetic graft vascular access.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p03] After 40 weeks following vaccination a protective effect was seen against *S. aureus* bacteremia, but not at 54 weeks following vaccination.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p03] Based on these results, a second trial was conducted which failed to show efficacy.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p03] Merck tested V710, a vaccine targeting IsdB, in a blinded randomized trial in patients undergoing median sternotomy.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p03] The trial was terminated after a higher rate of multiorgan system failure–related deaths was found in the V710 recipients.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p03] Vaccine recipients who developed *S. aureus* infection were five times more likely to die than control recipients who developed *S. aureus* infection.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p03] Investigators have suggested that a multiple-antigen vaccine would be more effective, but a lack of biomarkers defining human protective immunity keep these proposals in the logical, but strictly hypothetical arena.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p03] Antibodies show evidence against antimicrobial resistance.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p03] Monoclonal antibodies (mAbs) target bacterial virulence factors, aiding in bacterial destruction through various mechanisms.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p03] Three FDA-approved antibodies target *Bacillus anthracis* and *Clostridioides difficile* toxins.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p03] Alternating therapy is a proposed method in which two or three antibiotics are taken in a rotation versus taking just one antibiotic such that bacteria resistant to one antibiotic are killed when the next antibiotic is taken.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p03] Studies have found that this method reduces the rate at which antibiotic resistant bacteria emerge in vitro relative to a single drug for the entire duration.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p03] Studies have found that bacteria that evolve antibiotic resistance towards one group of antibiotic may become more sensitive to others.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p03] This phenomenon can be used to select against resistant bacteria using an approach termed collateral sensitivity cycling, which has recently been found to be relevant in developing treatment strategies for chronic infections caused by *Pseudomonas aeruginosa*.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p03] Despite its promise, large-scale clinical and experimental studies revealed limited evidence of susceptibility to antibiotic cycling across various pathogens.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p03] Another concern is that practitioners may become reluctant to perform routine surgeries because of the increased risk of harmful infection.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p03] Backup treatments can have serious side-effects; for example, antibiotics like aminoglycosides (such as amikacin, gentamicin, kanamycin, streptomycin, etc.) used for the treatment of drug-resistant tuberculosis and cystic fibrosis can cause respiratory disorders, deafness and kidney failure.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p03] The potential crisis at hand is the result of a marked decrease in industry research and development.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p03] Poor financial investment in antibiotic research has exacerbated the situation.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p03] In 2011, Pfizer, one of the last major pharmaceutical companies developing new antibiotics, shut down its primary research effort, citing poor shareholder returns relative to drugs for chronic illnesses.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p03] However, small and medium-sized pharmaceutical companies are still active in antibiotic drug research.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p03] In particular, apart from classical synthetic chemistry methodologies, researchers have developed a combinatorial synthetic biology platform on single cell level in a high-throughput screening manner to diversify novel lanthipeptides.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p03] In the 5–10 years since 2010, there has been a change in the ways new antimicrobial agents are discovered and developed – principally via the formation of public-private funding initiatives.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p03] Later stage clinical development is supported by the AMR Action Fund, which in turn is supported by multiple investors with the aim of developing 2–4 new antimicrobial agents by 2030.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p03] The discovery and development of new antimicrobial agents has been facilitated by regulatory advances, which have been principally led by the European Medicines Agency (EMA) and the Food and Drug Administration (FDA).
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p03] These processes are increasingly aligned although important differences remain and drug developers must prepare separate documents.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p03] New development pathways have been developed to help with the approval of new antimicrobial agents that address unmet needs such as the Limited Population Pathway for Antibacterial and Antifungal Drugs (LPAD).
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p03] These new pathways are required because of difficulties in conducting large definitive phase III clinical trials in a timely way.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p03] Some of the economic impediments to the development of new antimicrobial agents have been addressed by reimbursement schemes that delink payment of antimicrobials from volume-based sales.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p03] The available classes of antifungal drugs are still limited but as of 2021 novel classes of antifungals are being developed and are undergoing various stages of clinical trials to assess performance.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p03] Scientists have started using advanced computational approaches with supercomputers for the development of new antibiotic derivatives to deal with antimicrobial resistance.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p03] Using antibiotic-free alternatives in bone infection treatment may help decrease the use of antibiotics and thus antimicrobial resistance.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p03] The bone regeneration material bioactive glass S53P4 has shown to effectively inhibit the bacterial growth of up to 50 clinically relevant bacteria including MRSA and MRSE.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p03] During the last decades, copper and silver nanomaterials have demonstrated appealing features for the development of a new family of antimicrobial agents.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p03] Nanoparticles (1–100 nm) show unique properties and promise as antimicrobial agents against resistant bacteria.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p03] Silver (AgNPs) and gold nanoparticles (AuNPs) are extensively studied, disrupting bacterial cell membranes and interfering with protein synthesis.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p03] Zinc oxide (ZnO NPs), copper (CuNPs), and silica (SiNPs) nanoparticles also exhibit antimicrobial properties.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p03] However, high synthesis costs, potential toxicity, and instability pose challenges.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p03] To overcome these, biological synthesis methods and combination therapies with other antimicrobials are explored.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p03] Similar to the situation in malaria therapy, where successful treatments based on ancient recipes have been found, there has already been some success in finding and testing ancient drugs and other treatments that are effective against AMR bacteria.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p03] One of the key tools identified by the WHO and others for the fight against rising antimicrobial resistance is improved surveillance of the spread and movement of AMR genes through different communities and regions.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p03] Recent advances in high-throughput DNA sequencing as a result of the Human Genome Project have resulted in the ability to determine the individual microbial genes in a sample.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p03] Along with the availability of databases of known antimicrobial resistance genes, such as the Comprehensive Antimicrobial Resistance Database (CARD) and ResFinder, this allows the identification of all the antimicrobial resistance genes within the sample – the so-called "resistome".
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p03] In doing so, a profile of these genes within a community or environment can be determined, providing information into how antimicrobial resistance is spreading through a population and allowing for the identification of resistance that is of concern.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p03] Phage therapy is the therapeutic use of bacteriophages to treat pathogenic bacterial infections.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p03] Phage therapy has many potential applications in human medicine as well as dentistry, veterinary science, and agriculture.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p03] Phage therapy relies on the use of naturally occurring bacteriophages to infect and lyse bacteria at the site of infection in a host.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p03] Due to current advances in genetics and biotechnology these bacteriophages can possibly be manufactured to treat specific infections.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p03] Phages can be bioengineered to target multidrug-resistant bacterial infections, and their use involves the added benefit of preventing the elimination of beneficial bacteria in the human body.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p03] Phages destroy bacterial cell walls and membrane through the use of lytic proteins which kill bacteria by making many holes from the inside out.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p03] Bacteriophages can even possess the ability to digest the biofilm that many bacteria develop that protect them from antibiotics to effectively infect and kill bacteria.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p03] Bioengineering can play a role in creating successful bacteriophages.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p03] Understanding the mutual interactions and evolutions of bacterial and phage populations in the environment of a human or animal body is essential for rational phage therapy.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p03] Bacteriophagics are used against antibiotic resistant bacteria in Georgia (George Eliava Institute) and in one institute in Wrocław, Poland.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p03] Bacteriophage cocktails are common drugs sold over the counter in pharmacies in eastern countries.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p03] In Belgium, four patients with severe musculoskeletal infections received bacteriophage therapy with concomitant antibiotics.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p03] After a single course of phage therapy, no recurrence of infection occurred and no severe side-effects related to the therapy were detected.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p03] Analysing AMR data at scale requires dedicated computational approaches, as routine microbiological data from clinical laboratories can be large, heterogeneous, and subject to varying local standards.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p03] Several open-source tools have been developed to support this work.
[src:esther-lederberg/antibiotic-resistance-p03] The AMR package for R provides functions for standardising and analysing phenotypical resistance data, including interpretation of MIC and disk diffusion results against EUCAST and CLSI breakpoints, and calculation of resistance rates across patient populations.
[src:esther-lederberg/bacterial-conjugation] It is a mechanism of horizontal gene transfer as are transformation and transduction although these two other mechanisms do not involve cell-to-cell contact.
[src:esther-lederberg/bacterial-conjugation] Classical *E. coli* bacterial conjugation is often regarded as the bacterial equivalent of sexual reproduction or mating, since it involves the exchange of genetic material.
[src:esther-lederberg/bacterial-conjugation] However, it is not sexual reproduction, since no exchange of gamete occurs, and indeed no generation of a new organism: instead, an existing organism is transformed.
[src:esther-lederberg/bacterial-conjugation] During classical *E. coli* conjugation, the *donor* cell provides a conjugative or mobilizable genetic element that is most often a plasmid or transposon.
[src:esther-lederberg/bacterial-conjugation] Most conjugative plasmids have systems ensuring that the *recipient* cell does not already contain a similar element.
[src:esther-lederberg/bacterial-conjugation] The genetic information transferred is often beneficial to the recipient.
[src:esther-lederberg/bacterial-conjugation] Benefits may include antibiotic resistance, xenobiotic tolerance or the ability to use new metabolites.
[src:esther-lederberg/bacterial-conjugation] Other elements can be detrimental, and may be viewed as bacterial parasites.
[src:esther-lederberg/bacterial-conjugation] Conjugation in *Escherichia coli* by spontaneous zygogenesis and in *Mycobacterium smegmatis* by distributive conjugal transfer differ from the better studied classical *E. coli* conjugation in that these cases involve substantial blending of the parental genomes.
[src:esther-lederberg/bacterial-conjugation] The process was discovered by Joshua Lederberg and Edward Tatum in 1946.
[src:esther-lederberg/bacterial-conjugation] Pilus attaches to recipient cell and brings the two cells together.
[src:esther-lederberg/bacterial-conjugation] The mobile plasmid is nicked and a single strand of DNA is then transferred to the recipient cell.
[src:esther-lederberg/bacterial-conjugation] Both cells synthesize a complementary strand to produce a double stranded circular plasmid and also reproduce pili; both cells are now viable donors for the conjugative plasmid.
[src:esther-lederberg/bacterial-conjugation] The F-factor is an episome (a plasmid that can integrate itself into the bacterial chromosome by homologous recombination) with a length of about 100 kb.
[src:esther-lederberg/bacterial-conjugation] It is a classical example of a conjugative plasmid.
[src:esther-lederberg/bacterial-conjugation] It carries its own origin of replication, the *oriV*, and an origin of transfer, or *oriT*.
[src:esther-lederberg/bacterial-conjugation] There can only be one copy of the F-plasmid in a given bacterium, either free or integrated, and bacteria that possess a copy are called *F-positive* or *F-plus* (denoted F+).
[src:esther-lederberg/bacterial-conjugation] Cells that lack F plasmids are called *F-negative* or *F-minus* (F−) and as such can function as recipient cells.
[src:esther-lederberg/bacterial-conjugation] Among other genetic information, the F-plasmid carries a *tra* and *trb* locus, which together are about 33 kb long and consist of about 40 genes.
[src:esther-lederberg/bacterial-conjugation] The *tra* locus includes the *pilin* gene and regulatory genes, which together form pili on the cell surface.
[src:esther-lederberg/bacterial-conjugation] The locus also includes the genes for the proteins that attach themselves to the surface of F− bacteria and initiate conjugation.
[src:esther-lederberg/bacterial-conjugation] Though there is some debate on the exact mechanism of conjugation it seems that the pili are the structures through which DNA exchange occurs.
[src:esther-lederberg/bacterial-conjugation] The F-pili are extremely resistant to mechanical and thermochemical stress, which guarantees successful conjugation in a variety of environments.
[src:esther-lederberg/bacterial-conjugation] Several proteins coded for in the *tra* or *trb* locus seem to open a channel between the bacteria and it is thought that the TraD enzyme, located at the base of the pilus, initiates membrane fusion.
[src:esther-lederberg/bacterial-conjugation] When conjugation is initiated by a signal, the **relaxase** enzyme creates a nick in one of the strands of the conjugative plasmid at the *oriT*.
[src:esther-lederberg/bacterial-conjugation] Relaxase may work alone, or in a complex of over a dozen proteins known collectively as a **relaxosome**.
[src:esther-lederberg/bacterial-conjugation] In the F-plasmid system, the relaxase enzyme is called TraI and the relaxosome consists of TraI, TraY, TraM and the integrated host factor IHF.
[src:esther-lederberg/bacterial-conjugation] The nicked strand, or *T-strand*, is then unwound from the unbroken strand and transferred to the recipient cell in a 5'-terminus to 3'-terminus direction.
[src:esther-lederberg/bacterial-conjugation] The strand is thought to be transferred through the pilus into the recipient cell.
[src:esther-lederberg/bacterial-conjugation] The remaining strand is replicated either independent of conjugative action (vegetative replication beginning at the *oriV*) or in concert with conjugation (conjugative replication similar to the rolling circle replication of lambda phage).
[src:esther-lederberg/bacterial-conjugation] Conjugative replication may require a second nick before successful transfer can occur.
[src:esther-lederberg/bacterial-conjugation] A recent report claims to have inhibited conjugation with chemicals that mimic an intermediate step of this second nicking event.
[src:esther-lederberg/bacterial-conjugation] If the F-plasmid that is transferred has previously been integrated into the donor's genome (producing an Hfr strain ["High Frequency of Recombination"]) some of the donor's chromosomal DNA may also be transferred with the plasmid DNA.
[src:esther-lederberg/bacterial-conjugation] The amount of chromosomal DNA that is transferred depends on how long the two conjugating bacteria remain in contact.
[src:esther-lederberg/bacterial-conjugation] In common laboratory strains of *E. coli* the transfer of the entire bacterial chromosome takes about 100 minutes.
[src:esther-lederberg/bacterial-conjugation] The transferred DNA can then be integrated into the recipient genome via homologous recombination.
[src:esther-lederberg/bacterial-conjugation] A cell culture that contains in its population cells with non-integrated F-plasmids usually also contains a few cells that have integrated their plasmids.
[src:esther-lederberg/bacterial-conjugation] It is these cells that are responsible for the low-frequency chromosomal gene transfers that occur in such cultures.
[src:esther-lederberg/bacterial-conjugation] Some strains of bacteria with an integrated F-plasmid can be isolated and grown in pure culture.
[src:esther-lederberg/bacterial-conjugation] Because such strains transfer chromosomal genes very efficiently they are called **Hfr** (**h**igh **f**requency of **r**ecombination).
[src:esther-lederberg/bacterial-conjugation] The *E. coli* genome was originally mapped by interrupted mating experiments in which various Hfr cells in the process of conjugation were sheared from recipients after less than 100 minutes (initially using a Waring blender).
[src:esther-lederberg/bacterial-conjugation] The genes that were transferred were then investigated.
[src:esther-lederberg/bacterial-conjugation] In addition to classical bacterial conjugation described above for *E. coli*, a form of conjugation referred to as spontaneous zygogenesis (Z-mating for short) is observed in certain strains of *E. coli*.
[src:esther-lederberg/bacterial-conjugation] In Z-mating there is complete genetic mixing, and unstable diploids are formed that throw off phenotypically haploid cells, of which some show a parental phenotype and some are true recombinants.
[src:esther-lederberg/bacterial-conjugation] Conjugation in *Mycobacteria smegmatis*, like conjugation in *E. coli*, requires stable and extended contact between a donor and a recipient strain, is DNase resistant, and the transferred DNA is incorporated into the recipient chromosome by homologous recombination.
[src:esther-lederberg/bacterial-conjugation] However, unlike *E. coli* Hfr conjugation, mycobacterial conjugation is chromosome rather than plasmid based.
[src:esther-lederberg/bacterial-conjugation] Furthermore, in contrast to *E. coli* Hfr conjugation, in *M. smegmatis* all regions of the chromosome are transferred with comparable efficiencies.
[src:esther-lederberg/bacterial-conjugation] The lengths of the donor segments vary widely, but have an average length of 44.2kb.
[src:esther-lederberg/bacterial-conjugation] Since a mean of 13 tracts are transferred, the average total of transferred DNA per genome is 575kb.
[src:esther-lederberg/bacterial-conjugation] This process is referred to as "Distributive conjugal transfer." Gray et al. found substantial blending of the parental genomes as a result of conjugation and regarded this blending as reminiscent of that seen in the meiotic products of sexual reproduction.
[src:esther-lederberg/bacterial-conjugation] Hyperthermophilic archaea encode pili structurally similar to the bacterial conjugative pili.
[src:esther-lederberg/bacterial-conjugation] It has been suggested that in these archaea the conjugation machinery has been fully domesticated for promoting DNA repair through homologous recombination rather than spread of mobile genetic elements.
[src:esther-lederberg/bacterial-conjugation] In addition to the VirB2-like conjugative pilus, the Ced and Ted systems include components for the VirB6-like transmembrane mating pore and the VirB4-like ATPase.
[src:esther-lederberg/bacterial-conjugation] Bacteria related to the nitrogen fixing *Rhizobia* are an interesting case of inter-kingdom conjugation.
[src:esther-lederberg/bacterial-conjugation] For example, the tumor-inducing (Ti) plasmid of *Agrobacterium* and the root-tumor inducing (Ri) plasmid of *A. rhizogenes* contain genes that are capable of transferring to plant cells.
[src:esther-lederberg/bacterial-conjugation] The expression of these genes effectively transforms the plant cells into opine-producing factories.
[src:esther-lederberg/bacterial-conjugation] Opines are used by the bacteria as sources of nitrogen and energy.
[src:esther-lederberg/bacterial-conjugation] Infected cells form crown gall or root tumors.
[src:esther-lederberg/bacterial-conjugation] The Ti and Ri plasmids are thus endosymbionts of the bacteria, which are in turn endosymbionts (or parasites) of the infected plant.
[src:esther-lederberg/bacterial-conjugation] The Ti and Ri plasmids can also be transferred between bacteria using a system (the *tra*, or transfer, operon) that is different and independent of the system used for inter-kingdom transfer (the *vir*, or virulence, operon).
[src:esther-lederberg/bacterial-conjugation] Such transfers create virulent strains from previously avirulent strains.
[src:esther-lederberg/bacterial-conjugation] Conjugation is a convenient means for transferring genetic material to a variety of targets.
[src:esther-lederberg/bacterial-conjugation] In laboratories, successful transfers have been reported from bacteria to yeast, plants, mammalian cells, diatoms and isolated mammalian mitochondria.
[src:esther-lederberg/bacterial-conjugation] Conjugation has advantages over other forms of genetic transfer including minimal disruption of the target's cellular envelope and the ability to transfer relatively large genetic materials (see the above discussion of *E. coli* chromosome transfer).
[src:esther-lederberg/bacterial-conjugation] In plant engineering, *Agrobacterium*-like conjugation complements other standard vehicles such as tobacco mosaic virus (TMV).
[src:esther-lederberg/bacterial-conjugation] While TMV is capable of infecting many plant families these are primarily herbaceous dicots.
[src:esther-lederberg/bacterial-conjugation] *Agrobacterium*-like conjugation is also primarily used for dicots, but monocot recipients are not uncommon.
[src:esther-lederberg/bacteriophage] A **bacteriophage** (/bækˈtɪrioʊfeɪdʒ/), also known informally as a **phage** (/ˈfeɪdʒ/), is a virus that infects and replicates within bacteria.
[src:esther-lederberg/bacteriophage] The term is derived from Ancient Greek φαγεῖν*(phagein)* 'to devour' and *bacteria*.
[src:esther-lederberg/bacteriophage] Bacteriophages are composed of proteins that encapsulate a DNA or RNA genome, and may have structures that are either simple or elaborate.
[src:esther-lederberg/bacteriophage] Their genomes may encode as few as four genes (e.g.
[src:esther-lederberg/bacteriophage] Phages replicate within the bacterium following the injection of their genome into its cytoplasm.
[src:esther-lederberg/bacteriophage] Bacteriophages are among the most common and diverse entities in the biosphere.
[src:esther-lederberg/bacteriophage] Bacteriophages are ubiquitous viruses, found wherever bacteria exist.
[src:esther-lederberg/bacteriophage] It is estimated there are more than 1031 bacteriophages on the planet, more than every living organism on Earth, including bacteria, combined.
[src:esther-lederberg/bacteriophage] Bacteriophages were used from the 1920s as an alternative to antibiotics in the Soviet Union and Central Europe, as well as in France and Brazil.
[src:esther-lederberg/bacteriophage] They are seen as a possible therapy against multi-drug-resistant strains of many bacteria.
[src:esther-lederberg/bacteriophage] Bacteriophages are known to interact with the immune system both indirectly via bacterial expression of phage-encoded proteins and directly by influencing innate immunity and bacterial clearance.
[src:esther-lederberg/bacteriophage] Phage–host interactions are becoming increasingly important areas of research.
[src:esther-lederberg/bacteriophage] In 1896, Ernest Hanbury Hankin reported that something in the waters of the Ganges and Yamuna rivers in India had a marked antibacterial action against cholera and it could pass through a very fine porcelain Chamberland filter.
[src:esther-lederberg/bacteriophage] In 1915, British bacteriologist Frederick Twort, superintendent of the Brown Institution of London, discovered a small agent that infected and killed bacteria.
[src:esther-lederberg/bacteriophage] Twort's research was interrupted by the onset of World War I, as well as a shortage of funding and the discoveries of antibiotics.
[src:esther-lederberg/bacteriophage] Independently, French-Canadian microbiologist Félix d'Hérelle, working at the Pasteur Institute in Paris, announced on 3 September 1917 that he had discovered "an invisible, antagonistic microbe of the dysentery bacillus".
[src:esther-lederberg/bacteriophage] He also recorded a dramatic account of a man suffering from dysentery who was restored to good health by the bacteriophages.
[src:esther-lederberg/bacteriophage] It was d'Hérelle who conducted much research into bacteriophages and introduced the concept of phage therapy.
[src:esther-lederberg/bacteriophage] In 1919, in Paris, France, d'Hérelle conducted the first clinical application of a bacteriophage, with the first reported use in the United States being in 1922.
[src:esther-lederberg/bacteriophage] In 1969, Max Delbrück, Alfred Hershey, and Salvador Luria were awarded the Nobel Prize in Physiology or Medicine for their discoveries of the replication of viruses and their genetic structure.
[src:esther-lederberg/bacteriophage] Specifically the work of Hershey, as contributor to the Hershey–Chase experiment in 1952, provided convincing evidence that DNA, not protein, was the genetic material of life.
[src:esther-lederberg/bacteriophage] Delbrück and Luria carried out the Luria–Delbrück experiment which demonstrated statistically that mutations in bacteria occur randomly and thus follow Darwinian rather than Lamarckian principles.
[src:esther-lederberg/bacteriophage] In 2018, George Smith and Gregory Winter were awarded Nobel Prize in Chemistry for the phage display of peptides and antibodies.
[src:esther-lederberg/bacteriophage] Phages were discovered to be antibacterial agents and were used in the former Soviet Republic of Georgia (pioneered there by Giorgi Eliava with help from the co-discoverer of bacteriophages, Félix d'Hérelle) during the 1920s and 1930s for treating bacterial infections.
[src:esther-lederberg/bacteriophage] They had widespread use, including treatment of soldiers in the Red Army.
[src:esther-lederberg/bacteriophage] The use of phages has continued since the end of the Cold War in Russia, Georgia, and elsewhere in Central and Eastern Europe.
[src:esther-lederberg/bacteriophage] The first regulated, randomized, double-blind clinical trial was reported in the *Journal of Wound Care* in June 2009, which evaluated the safety and efficacy of a bacteriophage cocktail to treat infected venous ulcers of the leg in human patients.
[src:esther-lederberg/bacteriophage] The FDA approved the study as a Phase I clinical trial.
[src:esther-lederberg/bacteriophage] The study's results demonstrated the safety of therapeutic application of bacteriophages, but did not show efficacy.
[src:esther-lederberg/bacteriophage] The authors explained that the use of certain chemicals that are part of standard wound care (e.g. lactoferrin or silver) may have interfered with bacteriophage viability.
[src:esther-lederberg/bacteriophage] Shortly after that, another controlled clinical trial in Western Europe (treatment of ear infections caused by *Pseudomonas aeruginosa*) was reported in the journal *Clinical Otolaryngology* in August 2009.
[src:esther-lederberg/bacteriophage] The study concludes that bacteriophage preparations were safe and effective for treatment of chronic ear infections in humans.
[src:esther-lederberg/bacteriophage] Additionally, there have been numerous animal and other experimental clinical trials evaluating the efficacy of bacteriophages for various diseases, such as infected burns and wounds, and cystic fibrosis-associated lung infections, among others.
[src:esther-lederberg/bacteriophage] On the other hand, phages of *Inoviridae* have been shown to complicate biofilms involved in pneumonia and cystic fibrosis and to shelter the bacteria from drugs meant to eradicate disease, thus promoting persistent infection.
[src:esther-lederberg/bacteriophage] Meanwhile, bacteriophage researchers have been developing engineered viruses to overcome antibiotic resistance, and engineering the phage genes responsible for coding enzymes that degrade the biofilm matrix, phage structural proteins, and the enzymes responsible for lysis of the bacterial cell wall.
[src:esther-lederberg/bacteriophage] There have been results showing that T4 phages that are small in size and short-tailed can be helpful in detecting *E. coli* in the human body.
[src:esther-lederberg/bacteriophage] Therapeutic efficacy of a phage cocktail was evaluated in a mouse model with nasal infection of multi-drug-resistant (MDR) *A. baumannii*.
[src:esther-lederberg/bacteriophage] Mice treated with the phage cocktail showed a 2.3-fold higher survival rate compared to those untreated at seven days post-infection.
[src:esther-lederberg/bacteriophage] In 2017, a 68-year-old diabetic patient with necrotizing pancreatitis complicated by a pseudocyst infected with MDR *A. baumannii* strains was being treated with a cocktail of Azithromycin, Rifampicin, and Colistin for 4 months without results and overall rapidly declining health.
[src:esther-lederberg/bacteriophage] Once on the combination of the IV and PC therapy the patient's downward clinical trajectory reversed, and within two days he had awoken from his coma and become responsive.
[src:esther-lederberg/bacteriophage] As his immune system began to function he had to be temporarily removed from the cocktail because his fever was spiking to over 104 °F (40 °C), but after two days the phage cocktails were re-introduced at levels he was able to tolerate.
[src:esther-lederberg/bacteriophage] The original three-antibiotic cocktail was replaced by minocycline after the bacterial strain was found not to be resistant to this and he rapidly regained full lucidity, although he was not discharged from the hospital until roughly 145 days after phage therapy began.
[src:esther-lederberg/bacteriophage] Phages have increasingly been used to safen food products and to forestall spoilage bacteria.
[src:esther-lederberg/bacteriophage] Since 2006, the United States Food and Drug Administration (FDA) and United States Department of Agriculture (USDA) have approved several bacteriophage products.
[src:esther-lederberg/bacteriophage] LMP-102 (Intralytix) was approved for treating ready-to-eat (RTE) poultry and meat products.
[src:esther-lederberg/bacteriophage] In that same year, the FDA approved LISTEX (developed and produced by Micreos) using bacteriophages on cheese to kill *Listeria monocytogenes* bacteria, in order to give them generally recognized as safe (GRAS) status.
[src:esther-lederberg/bacteriophage] In July 2007, the same bacteriophage were approved for use on all food products.
[src:esther-lederberg/bacteriophage] In 2011 USDA confirmed that LISTEX is a clean label processing aid and is included in USDA.
[src:esther-lederberg/bacteriophage] Research in the field of food safety is continuing to see if lytic phages are a viable option to control other food-borne pathogens in various food products.
[src:esther-lederberg/bacteriophage] Switzerland authorized a phage for use in cheese production in 2016.
[src:esther-lederberg/bacteriophage] The European Union has not yet (2025) authorized any.
[src:esther-lederberg/bacteriophage] Bacteriophages, including those specific to *Escherichia coli*, have been employed as indicators of fecal contamination in water sources.
[src:esther-lederberg/bacteriophage] Due to their shared structural and biological characteristics, coliphages can serve as proxies for viral fecal contamination and the presence of pathogenic viruses such as rotavirus, norovirus, and HAV.
[src:esther-lederberg/bacteriophage] Research conducted on wastewater treatment systems has revealed significant disparities in the behavior of coliphages compared to fecal coliforms, demonstrating a distinct correlation with the recovery of pathogenic viruses at the treatment's conclusion.
[src:esther-lederberg/bacteriophage] Establishing a secure discharge threshold, studies have determined that discharges below 3000 PFU/100 mL are considered safe in terms of limiting the release of pathogenic viruses.
[src:esther-lederberg/bacteriophage] In 2011, the FDA cleared the first bacteriophage-based product for in vitro diagnostic use.
[src:esther-lederberg/bacteriophage] The KeyPath MRSA/MSSA Blood Culture Test uses a cocktail of bacteriophage to detect *Staphylococcus aureus* in positive blood cultures and determine methicillin resistance or susceptibility.
[src:esther-lederberg/bacteriophage] The test returns results in about five hours, compared to two to three days for standard microbial identification and susceptibility test methods.
[src:esther-lederberg/bacteriophage] It was the first accelerated antibiotic-susceptibility test approved by the FDA.
[src:esther-lederberg/bacteriophage] Government agencies in the West have for several years been looking to Georgia and the former Soviet Union for help with exploiting phages for counteracting bioweapons and toxins, such as anthrax and botulism.
[src:esther-lederberg/bacteriophage] Developments are continuing among research groups in the U.S.
[src:esther-lederberg/bacteriophage] Other uses include spray application in horticulture for protecting plants and vegetable produce from decay and the spread of bacterial disease.
[src:esther-lederberg/bacteriophage] Other applications for bacteriophages are as biocides for environmental surfaces, e.g., in hospitals, and as preventative treatments for catheters and medical devices before use in clinical settings.
[src:esther-lederberg/bacteriophage] The technology for phages to be applied to dry surfaces, e.g., uniforms, curtains, or even sutures for surgery now exists.
[src:esther-lederberg/bacteriophage] Clinical trials reported in *Clinical Otolaryngology* show success in veterinary treatment of pet dogs with otitis.
[src:esther-lederberg/bacteriophage] The sensing of phage-triggered ion cascades (SEPTIC) bacterium sensing and identification method uses the ion emission and its dynamics during phage infection and offers high specificity and speed for detection.
[src:esther-lederberg/bacteriophage] Phage display is a different use of phages involving a library of phages with a variable peptide linked to a surface protein.
[src:esther-lederberg/bacteriophage] Each phage genome encodes the variant of the protein displayed on its surface (hence the name), providing a link between the peptide variant and its encoding gene.
[src:esther-lederberg/bacteriophage] Variant phages from the library may be selected through their binding affinity to an immobilized molecule (e.g., botulism toxin) to neutralize it.
[src:esther-lederberg/bacteriophage] The bound, selected phages can be multiplied by reinfecting a susceptible bacterial strain, thus allowing them to retrieve the peptides encoded in them for further study.
[src:esther-lederberg/bacteriophage] Phage proteins often have antimicrobial activity and may serve as leads for peptidomimetics, i.e. drugs that mimic peptides.
[src:esther-lederberg/bacteriophage] Phage-ligand technology makes use of phage proteins for various applications, such as binding of bacteria and bacterial components (e.g. endotoxin) and lysis of bacteria.
[src:esther-lederberg/bacteriophage] Bacteriophages are important model organisms for studying principles of evolution and ecology.
[src:esther-lederberg/bacteriophage] Phages can be used to combat bacterial infections such as blackleg.
[src:esther-lederberg/bacteriophage] A line of phage-based products is licensed in the United States, and Georgia has long used agricultural phages.
[src:esther-lederberg/bacteriophage] Elsewhere, research and pilot testing are still underway.
[src:esther-lederberg/bacteriophage] This is notably the case in Switzerland, where research is being conducted by the Fribourg School of Engineering and Architecture in collaboration with the Lausanne University Hospital (CHUV).
[src:esther-lederberg/bacteriophage] Bacteriophages present in the environment can cause cheese to not ferment.
[src:esther-lederberg/bacteriophage] In order to avoid this, mixed-strain starter cultures and culture rotation regimes can be used.
[src:esther-lederberg/bacteriophage] Genetic engineering of culture microbes – especially *Lactococcus lactis* and *Streptococcus thermophilus* – have been studied for genetic analysis and modification to improve phage resistance.
[src:esther-lederberg/bacteriophage] This has especially focused on plasmid and recombinant chromosomal modifications.
[src:esther-lederberg/bacteriophage] Some research has focused on the potential of bacteriophages as antimicrobial against foodborne pathogens and biofilm formation within the dairy industry.
[src:esther-lederberg/bacteriophage] As the spread of antibiotic resistance is a main concern within the dairy industry, phages can serve as a promising alternative.
[src:esther-lederberg/bacteriophage] The life cycle of bacteriophages tends to be either a lytic cycle or a lysogenic cycle.
[src:esther-lederberg/bacteriophage] In addition, some phages display pseudolysogenic behaviors.
[src:esther-lederberg/bacteriophage] With *lytic phages* such as the T4 phage, bacterial cells are broken open (lysed) and destroyed after immediate replication of the virion.
[src:esther-lederberg/bacteriophage] As soon as the cell is destroyed, the phage progeny can find new hosts to infect.
[src:esther-lederberg/bacteriophage] Lytic phages are more suitable for phage therapy.
[src:esther-lederberg/bacteriophage] Some lytic phages undergo a phenomenon known as lysis inhibition, where completed phage progeny will not immediately lyse out of the cell if extracellular phage concentrations are high.
[src:esther-lederberg/bacteriophage] This mechanism is not identical to that of the temperate phage going dormant and usually is temporary.
[src:esther-lederberg/bacteriophage] In contrast, the *lysogenic cycle* does not result in immediate lysing of the host cell.
[src:esther-lederberg/bacteriophage] Those phages able to undergo lysogeny are known as temperate phages.
[src:esther-lederberg/bacteriophage] Their viral genome will integrate with host DNA and replicate along with it, relatively harmlessly, or may even become established as a plasmid.
[src:esther-lederberg/bacteriophage] The virus remains dormant until host conditions deteriorate, perhaps due to depletion of nutrients, then, the endogenous phages (known as prophages) become active.
[src:esther-lederberg/bacteriophage] At this point they initiate the reproductive cycle, resulting in lysis of the host cell.
[src:esther-lederberg/bacteriophage] As the lysogenic cycle allows the host cell to continue to survive and reproduce, the virus is replicated in all offspring of the cell.
[src:esther-lederberg/bacteriophage] Sometimes prophages may provide benefits to the host bacterium while they are dormant by adding new functions to the bacterial genome, in a phenomenon called lysogenic conversion.
[src:esther-lederberg/bacteriophage] Examples are the conversion of harmless strains of *Corynebacterium diphtheriae* or *Vibrio cholerae* by bacteriophages to highly virulent ones that cause diphtheria or cholera, respectively.
[src:esther-lederberg/bacteriophage] Strategies to combat certain bacterial infections by targeting these toxin-encoding prophages have been proposed.
[src:esther-lederberg/bacteriophage] Bacterial cells are protected by a cell wall of polysaccharides, which are important virulence factors protecting bacterial cells against both immune host defenses and antibiotics.
[src:esther-lederberg/bacteriophage] To enter a host cell, bacteriophages bind to specific receptors on the surface of bacteria, including lipopolysaccharides, teichoic acids, proteins, or even flagella.
[src:esther-lederberg/bacteriophage] This specificity means a bacteriophage can infect only certain bacteria bearing receptors to which they can bind, which in turn, determines the phage's host range.
[src:esther-lederberg/bacteriophage] Polysaccharide-degrading enzymes are virion-associated proteins that enzymatically degrade the capsular outer layer of their hosts at the initial step of a tightly programmed phage infection process.
[src:esther-lederberg/bacteriophage] Host growth conditions also influence the ability of the phage to attach and invade them.
[src:esther-lederberg/bacteriophage] As phage virions do not move independently, they must rely on random encounters with the correct receptors when in solution, such as blood, lymphatic circulation, irrigation, soil water, etc.
[src:esther-lederberg/bacteriophage] Myovirus bacteriophages use a hypodermic syringe-like motion to inject their genetic material into the cell.
[src:esther-lederberg/bacteriophage] After contacting the appropriate receptor, the tail fibers flex to bring the base plate closer to the surface of the cell.
[src:esther-lederberg/bacteriophage] Once attached completely, irreversible binding is initiated and the tail contracts, possibly with the help of ATP present in the tail, injecting genetic material through the bacterial membrane.
[src:esther-lederberg/bacteriophage] The injection is accomplished through a sort of bending motion in the shaft by going to the side, contracting closer to the cell and pushing back up.
[src:esther-lederberg/bacteriophage] Podoviruses lack an elongated tail sheath like that of a myovirus, so instead, they use their small, tooth-like tail fibers enzymatically to degrade a portion of the cell membrane before inserting their genetic material.
[src:esther-lederberg/bacteriophage] Within minutes, bacterial ribosomes start translating viral mRNA into protein.
[src:esther-lederberg/bacteriophage] For RNA-based phages, RNA replicase is synthesized early in the process.
[src:esther-lederberg/bacteriophage] Proteins modify the bacterial RNA polymerase so it preferentially transcribes viral mRNA.
[src:esther-lederberg/bacteriophage] The host's normal synthesis of proteins and nucleic acids is disrupted, and it is forced to manufacture viral products instead.
[src:esther-lederberg/bacteriophage] These products go on to become part of new virions within the cell, helper proteins that contribute to the assemblage of new virions, or proteins involved in cell lysis.
[src:esther-lederberg/bacteriophage] In 1972, Walter Fiers (University of Ghent, Belgium) was the first to establish the complete nucleotide sequence of a gene and in 1976, of the viral genome of bacteriophage MS2.
[src:esther-lederberg/bacteriophage] Some dsDNA bacteriophages encode ribosomal proteins, which are thought to modulate protein translation during phage infection.
[src:esther-lederberg/bacteriophage] In the case of the T4 phage, the construction of new virus particles involves the assistance of helper proteins that act catalytically during phage morphogenesis.
[src:esther-lederberg/bacteriophage] The base plates are assembled first, with the tails being built upon them afterward.
[src:esther-lederberg/bacteriophage] The head capsids, constructed separately, will spontaneously assemble with the tails.
[src:esther-lederberg/bacteriophage] During assembly of the phage T4 virion, the morphogenetic proteins encoded by the phage genes interact with each other in a characteristic sequence.
[src:esther-lederberg/bacteriophage] Maintaining an appropriate balance in the amounts of each of these proteins produced during viral infection appears to be critical for normal phage T4 morphogenesis.
[src:esther-lederberg/bacteriophage] The DNA is packed efficiently within the heads.
[src:esther-lederberg/bacteriophage] The whole process takes about 15 minutes.
[src:esther-lederberg/bacteriophage] Early studies of bacteriophage T4 (1962–1964) provided an opportunity to gain understanding of virtually all of the genes that are essential for growth of the bacteriophage under laboratory conditions.
[src:esther-lederberg/bacteriophage] These studies were made possible by the availability of two classes of conditional lethal mutants.
[src:esther-lederberg/bacteriophage] One class of such mutants was referred to as amber mutants.
[src:esther-lederberg/bacteriophage] The other class of conditional lethal mutants was referred to as temperature-sensitive mutants.
[src:esther-lederberg/bacteriophage] Studies of these two classes of mutants led to considerable insight into the functions and interactions of the proteins employed in the machinery of DNA replication, repair and recombination, and on how viruses are assembled from protein and nucleic acid components (molecular morphogenesis).
[src:esther-lederberg/bacteriophage] Phages may be released via cell lysis, by extrusion, or, in a few cases, by budding.
[src:esther-lederberg/bacteriophage] Lysis, by tailed phages, is achieved by an enzyme called endolysin, which attacks and breaks down the cell wall peptidoglycan.
[src:esther-lederberg/bacteriophage] An altogether different phage type, the filamentous phage, makes the host cell continually secrete new virus particles.
[src:esther-lederberg/bacteriophage] Released virions are described as free, and, unless defective, are capable of infecting a new bacterium.
[src:esther-lederberg/bacteriophage] Budding is associated with certain *Mycoplasma* phages.
[src:esther-lederberg/bacteriophage] In contrast to virion release, phages displaying a lysogenic cycle do not kill the host and instead become long-term residents as prophages.
[src:esther-lederberg/bacteriophage] Research in 2017 revealed that the bacteriophage Φ3T makes a short viral protein that signals other bacteriophages to lie dormant instead of killing the host bacterium.
[src:esther-lederberg/bacteriophage] Arbitrium is the name given to this protein by the researchers who discovered it.
[src:esther-lederberg/bacteriophage] Given the millions of different phages in the environment, phage genomes come in a variety of forms and sizes.
[src:esther-lederberg/bacteriophage] RNA phages such as MS2 have the smallest genomes, with only a few kilobases.
[src:esther-lederberg/bacteriophage] However, some DNA phages such as T4 may have large genomes with hundreds of genes; the size and shape of the capsid varies along with the size of the genome.
[src:esther-lederberg/bacteriophage] The largest bacteriophage genomes reach a size of 735 kb.
[src:esther-lederberg/bacteriophage] Bacteriophage genomes can be highly mosaic, i.e. the genome of many phage species appear to be composed of numerous individual modules.
[src:esther-lederberg/bacteriophage] These modules may be found in other phage species in different arrangements.
[src:esther-lederberg/bacteriophage] Mycobacteriophages, bacteriophages with mycobacterial hosts, have provided excellent examples of this mosaicism.
[src:esther-lederberg/bacteriophage] In these mycobacteriophages, genetic assortment may be the result of repeated instances of site-specific recombination and illegitimate recombination (the result of phage genome acquisition of bacterial host genetic sequences).
[src:esther-lederberg/bacteriophage] Evolutionary mechanisms shaping the genomes of bacterial viruses vary between different families and depend upon the type of the nucleic acid, characteristics of the virion structure, as well as the mode of the viral life cycle.
[src:esther-lederberg/bacteriophage] Some marine roseobacter phages, also known as roseophages, contain deoxyuridine (dU) instead of deoxythymidine (dT) in their genomic DNA.
[src:esther-lederberg/bacteriophage] There is some evidence that this unusual component is a mechanism to evade bacterial defense mechanisms such as restriction endonucleases and CRISPR/Cas systems which evolved to recognize and cleave sequences within invading phages, thereby inactivating them.
[src:esther-lederberg/bacteriophage] Other phages have long been known to use unusual nucleotides.
[src:esther-lederberg/bacteriophage] In 1963, Takahashi and Marmur identified a *Bacillus* phage that has dU substituting dT in its genome, and in 1977, Kirnos et al. identified a cyanophage containing 2-aminoadenine (Z) instead of adenine (A).
[src:esther-lederberg/bacteriophage] The field of systems biology investigates the complex networks of interactions within an organism, usually using computational tools and modeling.
[src:esther-lederberg/bacteriophage] For example, a phage genome that enters into a bacterial host cell may express hundreds of phage proteins which will affect the expression of numerous host genes or the host's metabolism.
[src:esther-lederberg/bacteriophage] All of these complex interactions can be described and simulated in computer models.
[src:esther-lederberg/bacteriophage] For instance, infection of *Pseudomonas aeruginosa* by the temperate phage PaP3 changed the expression of 38% (2160/5633) of its host's genes.
[src:esther-lederberg/bacteriophage] Many of these effects are probably indirect, hence the challenge becomes to identify the direct interactions among bacteria and phage.
[src:esther-lederberg/bacteriophage] Several attempts have been made to map protein–protein interactions among phage and their host.
[src:esther-lederberg/bacteriophage] For instance, bacteriophage lambda was found to interact with its host, *E. coli*, by dozens of interactions.
[src:esther-lederberg/bacteriophage] Again, the significance of many of these interactions remains unclear, but these studies suggest that there most likely are several key interactions and many indirect interactions whose role remains uncharacterized.
[src:esther-lederberg/bacteriophage] Bacteriophages are a major threat to bacteria and prokaryotes, which have evolved numerous mechanisms to block infection (host resistance) or to block the replication of bacteriophages within host cells (anti-phage defense).
[src:esther-lederberg/bacteriophage] Temperate phages are bacteriophages that integrate their genetic material into the host as extrachromosomal episomes or as a prophage during a lysogenic cycle.
[src:esther-lederberg/bacteriophage] Bacteriophage–host symbiosis may benefit bacteria by providing selective advantages while passively replicating the phage genome.
[src:esther-lederberg/bacteriophage] Metagenomics has allowed the in-water detection of bacteriophages that was not possible previously.
[src:esther-lederberg/bacteriophage] Also, bacteriophages have been used in hydrological tracing and modelling in river systems, especially where surface water and groundwater interactions occur.
[src:esther-lederberg/bacteriophage] The use of phages is preferred to the more conventional dye marker because they are significantly less absorbed when passing through ground waters and they are readily detected at very low concentrations.
[src:esther-lederberg/bacteriophage] Non-polluted water may contain approximately 2×108 bacteriophages per ml.
[src:esther-lederberg/bacteriophage] Bacteriophages are thought to contribute extensively to horizontal gene transfer in natural environments, principally via transduction, but also via transformation.
[src:esther-lederberg/bacteriophage] Metagenomics-based studies also have revealed that viromes from a variety of environments harbor antibiotic-resistance genes, including those that could confer multidrug resistance.
[src:esther-lederberg/bacteriophage] Recent findings have mapped the complex and intertwined arsenal of anti-phage defense tools in environmental bacteria.
[src:esther-lederberg/bacteriophage] Although phages do not infect humans, there are countless phage particles in the human body, given the extensive human microbiome.
[src:esther-lederberg/bacteriophage] One's phage population has been called the human phageome, including the "healthy gut phageome" (HGP) and the "diseased human phageome" (DHP).
[src:esther-lederberg/bacteriophage] The active phageome of a healthy human (i.e., actively replicating as opposed to nonreplicating, integrated prophage) has been estimated to comprise dozens to thousands of different viruses.
[src:esther-lederberg/bacteriophage] There is evidence that bacteriophages and bacteria interact in the human gut microbiome both antagonistically and beneficially.
[src:esther-lederberg/bacteriophage] Preliminary studies have indicated that common bacteriophages are found in 62% of healthy individuals on average, while their prevalence was reduced by 42% and 54% on average in patients with ulcerative colitis (UC) and Crohn's disease (CD).
[src:esther-lederberg/bacteriophage] Abundance of phages may also decline in the elderly.
[src:esther-lederberg/bacteriophage] The most common phages in the human intestine, found worldwide, are crAssphages.
[src:esther-lederberg/bacteriophage] CrAssphages are transmitted from mother to child soon after birth, and there is some evidence suggesting that they may be transmitted locally.
[src:esther-lederberg/bacteriophage] Each person develops their own unique crAssphage clusters.
[src:esther-lederberg/bacteriophage] CrAss-like phages also may be present in primates besides humans.
[src:esther-lederberg/bacteriophage] Among the countless phages, only a few have been studied in detail, including some historically important phages that were discovered in the early days of microbial genetics.
[src:esther-lederberg/bacteriophage] These, especially the T-phage, helped to discover important principles of gene structure and function.
[src:esther-lederberg/bernard-ogilvie-dodge] Dodge's work on the genetics of *Neurospora* laid the groundwork for the discoveries that earned George Wells Beadle and Edward Lawrie Tatum the Nobel Prize in 1958.
[src:esther-lederberg/bernard-ogilvie-dodge] Bernard Ogilvie Dodge was an eighth-generation descendant of Rebecca Nurse, the third of seven children born to Mary Ann and Elbridge Gerry Dodge.
[src:esther-lederberg/bernard-ogilvie-dodge] Though neither parent had a high school education, both had a strong love for literature, music and learning.
[src:esther-lederberg/bernard-ogilvie-dodge] Dodge's father was widely acquainted with the writings of Shakespeare, Byron, Chaucer, Spenser, and Pope, and supplemented the income from his Mauston, Wisconsin farm by teaching in the local schools.
[src:esther-lederberg/bernard-ogilvie-dodge] Bernard Dodge spent the first 20 years of his life working on the family farm.
[src:esther-lederberg/bernard-ogilvie-dodge] Robbins that at the age of 10 a bumper crop of sorghum required operation of the mill day and night during the rush period of syrup making.
[src:esther-lederberg/bernard-ogilvie-dodge] At such times Dodge's father, two of Dodge's older brothers, and Dodge worked 18 hours a day, beginning at midnight.
[src:esther-lederberg/bernard-ogilvie-dodge] (Dodge's job was to stand on the circling horsepower platform and drive the horses, walking sideways to avoid dizziness.) That same winter, Bernard Dodge also worked at the local schoolhouse, one mile away, to sweep out the schoolhouse and build the fire.
[src:esther-lederberg/bernard-ogilvie-dodge] Dodge did not complete his high school education until he was 20 years old.
[src:esther-lederberg/bernard-ogilvie-dodge] He taught high school and then entered the University of Wisconsin as a special student in 1896, only to leave college less than a year later when his funds were exhausted.
[src:esther-lederberg/bernard-ogilvie-dodge] He returned to teaching until, at the age of 28, he had saved enough money to resume his formal education.
[src:esther-lederberg/bernard-ogilvie-dodge] He obtained a diploma from Milwaukee Normal School, returned to teaching a third time (serving as high school principal at Algoma, Wisconsin, where he also taught botany, physics and geometry).
[src:esther-lederberg/bernard-ogilvie-dodge] Dodge returned to the University of Wisconsin in 1908, at the age of 36, and completed the requirements for the Ph.B. degree in 1909.
[src:esther-lederberg/bernard-ogilvie-dodge] In high school, Dodge had a three-month course in botany in which each student was required to collect and identify 75 plants, using the keys of Gray's "School and Field Botany" textbook.
[src:esther-lederberg/bernard-ogilvie-dodge] Robbins that he "far exceeded the number required".
[src:esther-lederberg/bernard-ogilvie-dodge] While still a high school principal in Algoma, a chance meeting with an amateur mycologist (a Bohemian tailor with a basket full of "Pilze" (mushrooms) that were "gut fur essen" (good to eat)) aroused an interest in collecting fungi.
[src:esther-lederberg/bernard-ogilvie-dodge] Dodge sent specimens to the University of Wisconsin for identification, bought Atkinson's book on mushrooms, and his wife Jennie presented him with MacIllwain's "One Thousand Edible Mushrooms" as a Christmas present.
[src:esther-lederberg/bernard-ogilvie-dodge] At the University of Wisconsin, Dodge studied Botany under R.
[src:esther-lederberg/bernard-ogilvie-dodge] When Harper transferred to Columbia University in New York, he suggested that Dodge undertake graduate work there.
[src:esther-lederberg/bernard-ogilvie-dodge] Dodge accepted a minor position as an Assistant and Research Fellow in Botany at Columbia.
[src:esther-lederberg/bernard-ogilvie-dodge] Dodge received his Ph.D at the age of 40; his first paper was published when he was 42.
[src:esther-lederberg/bernard-ogilvie-dodge] Dodge remained at Columbia as Instructor of Botany until 1920, when he accepted an appointment as Plant Pathologist (in fruit diseases) in the Bureau of Plant Industry of the U.S.
[src:esther-lederberg/bernard-ogilvie-dodge] During his eight years in Washington, D.C., he initiated his studies of *Neurospora*.
[src:esther-lederberg/bernard-ogilvie-dodge] As a graduate student and instructor at Columbia, Dodge investigated the taxonomy and reproduction of species of Ascobolaceae.
[src:esther-lederberg/bernard-ogilvie-dodge] He found that the ascospores of several species of Ascobolus which rarely germinate under ordinary conditions on artificial media, do so readily after being subjected to 50-70 degrees Celsius for five to 10 minutes.
[src:esther-lederberg/bernard-ogilvie-dodge] Dodge discovered this completely by accident: after trying several methods to germinate the ascospores of Ascobolus (without success).
[src:esther-lederberg/bernard-ogilvie-dodge] One day Dodge temporarily set down a batch of test plates inside a hot-air sterilizer which was not running, while he went to teach a class.
[src:esther-lederberg/bernard-ogilvie-dodge] When Dodge returned, he was dismayed to find that someone had lit the oven in the interim, and the temperature inside had reached over 70 degrees.
[src:esther-lederberg/bernard-ogilvie-dodge] Dodge removed the plates, assumed that the spores had been killed, but before discarding the old plates he examined them under a microscope.
[src:esther-lederberg/bernard-ogilvie-dodge] He was astounded to find that most of the spores had germinated.
[src:esther-lederberg/bernard-ogilvie-dodge] This discovery proved to be of importance later for his studies of *Neurospora*.
[src:esther-lederberg/bernard-ogilvie-dodge] Though Dodge considered himself primarily a mycologist and a plant pathologist, his study of *Neurospora* is regarded by many as his major work.
[src:esther-lederberg/bernard-ogilvie-dodge] The ability to germinate the ascospores of *Neurospora* made it possible to define its life cycle, distinguish species, make crosses between species, and grow the haploid offspring.
[src:esther-lederberg/bernard-ogilvie-dodge] Over the next 30 years, Dodge published over 40 papers on *Neurospora*, which was easy to grow and required little space (and only a few days) to complete its life cycle.
[src:esther-lederberg/bernard-ogilvie-dodge] These advantages made *Neurospora*, in many respects, an ideal organism for the investigation of genetics and biochemical genetics.
[src:esther-lederberg/bernard-ogilvie-dodge] Dodge convinced Thomas Hunt Morgan of the advantages of *Neurospora* and Morgan took cultures with him when he transferred from Columbia University to the California Institute of Technology in 1928.
[src:esther-lederberg/bernard-ogilvie-dodge] Dodge never developed a larger program involving an extensive study of spontaneous and induced mutations or chromosome mapping.
[src:esther-lederberg/bernard-ogilvie-dodge] In fact, he regarded his research on *Neurospora* as an "extra", carried on while pursuing his official duties as a plant pathologist.
[src:esther-lederberg/bernard-ogilvie-dodge] Nevertheless, Dodge's investigations laid the foundation for the use of *Neurospora* in the investigation of genetics and biochemical genetics on a worldwide basis.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p01] The Bronx is divided by the Bronx River into a hillier section in the west and a flatter eastern section.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p01] East and west street names are divided by Jerome Avenue.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p01] The west was annexed to New York City in 1874, and the areas east of the Bronx River in 1895.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p01] Bronx County was separated from New York County (modern-day Manhattan) in 1914.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p01] About a quarter of the Bronx's area is open space, including Woodlawn Cemetery, Van Cortlandt Park, Pelham Bay Park, the New York Botanical Garden, and the Bronx Zoo in the borough's north and center.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p01] The Thain Family Forest at the New York Botanical Garden is thousands of years old and is New York City's largest remaining tract of the original forest that once covered the city.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p01] These open spaces are primarily on land reserved in the late 19th century as urban development progressed north and east from Manhattan.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p01] The Bronx is also home to Yankee Stadium of Major League Baseball.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p01] The word Bronx originated with Jonas Bronck, who established the first European settlement in the area as part of the New Netherland colony in 1639.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p01] European settlers displaced the native Lenape after 1643.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p01] African American migrants from the Southern United States as well as Panamanians, Hondurans, and South Asians also established themselves in the borough in large numbers.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p01] The Bronx contains what had been the poorest of all 435 U.S. congressional districts, New York's 15th, until redistricting following the 2020 census.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p01] The borough also features upper- and middle-income neighborhoods, such as Riverdale, Fieldston, Spuyten Duyvil, Schuylerville, Pelham Bay, Pelham Gardens, Morris Park, and Country Club.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p01] Parts of the Bronx saw a steep decline in population, livable housing, and quality of life starting from the mid-to-late 1960s and lasting well into the 1980s, including a wave of arson in the late 1970s.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p01] The South Bronx, in particular, experienced severe urban decay.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p01] The borough began experiencing new population growth starting in the late 1990s and continuing to the present day.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p01] The Bronx was called **Rananchqua** by the native Siwanoy band of Lenape, also known historically as *the Delawares*.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p01] Other Native Americans knew the Bronx as *Keskeskeck*.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p01] It was divided by the Aquahung River (now known in English as the Bronx River).
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p01] The "Bronx" name derives from Jonas Bronck (c.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p01] 1600–1643), a European settler whose precise origins are disputed.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p01] Documents indicate he was a Swedish-born immigrant from Komstad, Norra Ljunga parish in Småland, Sweden, who arrived in New Netherland during the spring of 1639.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p01] Bronck became the first recorded European settler in the present-day Bronx and built a farm named "Emmaus" close to what today is the corner of Willis Avenue and 132nd Street in Mott Haven.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p01] He leased land from the Dutch West India Company on the neck of the mainland immediately north of the Dutch settlement of New Haarlem (on Manhattan Island), and bought additional tracts from the local tribes.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p01] He eventually accumulated 500 acres (200 ha) between the Harlem River and the Aquahung, which became known as *Bronck's River* or *the Bronx River*.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p01] Dutch and English settlers referred to the area as *Bronck's Land*.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p01] The American poet William Bronk was a descendant of Pieter Bronck, probably Jonas Bronck's nephew or cousin, as there was an age difference of 16 years.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p01] Much work on the Swedish claim has been undertaken by Brian G.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p01] Andersson, former Commissioner of New York City's Department of Records, who helped organize a 375th Anniversary celebration in Bronck's hometown in 2014.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p01] The Bronx is referred to with the definite article as "the Bronx" or "The Bronx", both legally and colloquially.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p01] The "County of the Bronx" also takes "the" immediately before "Bronx" in formal references, like the coextensive "Borough of the Bronx".
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p01] The United States Postal Service uses "Bronx, NY" for mailing addresses.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p01] The definite article comes from the Bronx River and first appeared in the "Annexed District of The Bronx", created in 1874 out of part of Westchester County.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p01] It was continued in the "Borough of The Bronx", created in 1898, which included a larger annexation from Westchester County in 1895.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p01] The use of the definite article is attributed to the style of referring to rivers.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p01] A time-worn story purportedly explaining the use of the definite article in the borough's name says it stems from the phrase "visiting the Broncks", referring to the settler's family.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p01] The capitalization of the borough's name is sometimes disputed.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p01] Generally, the definite article is lowercase in place names ("the Bronx") except in some official references.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p01] The definite article is capitalized ("The Bronx") at the beginning of a sentence or in any other situation when a normally lowercase word would be capitalized.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p01] Some people and groups refer to the borough with a capital letter at all times, such as Bronx Borough Historian Lloyd Ultan, The Bronx County Historical Society, and the Bronx-based organization Great and Glorious Grand Army of The Bronx, arguing the definite article is part of the proper name.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p01] In particular, the Great and Glorious Grand Army of The Bronx is leading efforts to make the city refer to the borough with an uppercase definite article in all uses, comparing the lowercase article in the Bronx's name to "not capitalizing the 's' in 'Staten Island'".
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p01] Originally, the area was part of the Lenape's Lenapehoking territory inhabited by Siwanoy of the Wappinger Confederacy.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p01] European colonization of the Bronx began in 1639.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p01] Over time, European colonists converted the area into farmlands.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p01] The Bronx was originally part of Westchester County, but it was ceded to New York City in two major parts (the West Bronx in 1874 and the East Bronx in 1895), subsequently becoming Bronx County.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p01] The Bronx's development is directly connected to its strategic location between New England and New York (Manhattan).
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p01] Control over the bridges across the Harlem River plagued the period of British colonial rule.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p01] The King's Bridge, built in 1693 where Broadway reached the Spuyten Duyvil Creek, was a possession of Frederick Philipse, lord of Philipse Manor.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p01] Local farmers on both sides of the creek resented the tolls, and in 1759, Jacobus Dyckman and Benjamin Palmer led them in building a free bridge across the Harlem River.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p01] After the American Revolutionary War, the King's Bridge toll was abolished.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p01] The territory now contained within Bronx County was originally part of Westchester County, one of the 12 original counties of the English Province of New York.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p01] The present Bronx County was contained in the town of Westchester and parts of the towns of Yonkers, Eastchester, and Pelham.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p01] In 1846, a new town was created by division of Westchester, called West Farms.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p01] The town of Morrisania was created, in turn, from West Farms in 1855.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p01] In 1873, the town of Kingsbridge was established within the former borders of the town of Yonkers, roughly corresponding to the modern Bronx neighborhoods of Kingsbridge, Riverdale, and Woodlawn Heights, and included Woodlawn Cemetery.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p01] Among the famous people who settled in the Bronx during the 19th and early 20th centuries were author Willa Cather, tobacco merchant Pierre Lorillard, and inventor Jordan L.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p01] Mott, who established Mott Haven to house the workers at his iron works.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p01] The consolidation of the Bronx into New York City proceeded in two stages.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p01] In 1873, the state legislature annexed Kingsbridge, West Farms, and Morrisania to New York, effective in 1874; the three towns were soon abolished in the process.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p01] In 1895, the whole territory east of the Bronx River was annexed to the city three years before New York's consolidation with Brooklyn, Queens, and Staten Island.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p01] This included the Town of Westchester, which had voted against consolidation in 1894, and parts of Eastchester and Pelham.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p01] The maritime community of City Island voted to join the city in 1896.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p01] Following these two annexations, the Bronx's territory had moved from Westchester County into New York County, which already included Manhattan and the rest of pre-1874 New York City.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p01] On January 1, 1898, the consolidated City of New York was born, including the Bronx as one of the five distinct boroughs.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p01] It remained part of New York County until Bronx County was created in 1914.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p01] On April 19, 1912, those parts of New York County which had been annexed from Westchester County in previous decades were newly constituted as Bronx County, the 62nd and last county to be created by the state, effective in 1914.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p01] Bronx County's courts opened for business on January 2, 1914, the same day that John P.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p01] Mitchel started work as Mayor of New York City.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p01] Marble Hill, Manhattan, was now connected to the Bronx by filling in the former waterway, but it is not part of the borough or Bronx county.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p01] The history of the Bronx during the 20th century may be divided into four periods: a boom period during 1900–1929, with a population growth by a factor of six from 200,000 in 1900 to 1.3 million in 1930.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p01] The Great Depression and post-World War II years saw a slowing of growth leading into an eventual decline.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p01] The mid to late century were hard times, as the Bronx changed during 1950–1985 from a predominantly moderate-income to a predominantly lower-income area with high rates of violent crime and poverty in some areas.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p01] The Bronx has experienced an economic and developmental resurgence starting in the late 1980s that continues into today.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p01] The Bronx was a mostly rural area for many generations, with small farms supplying the city markets.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p01] In the late 19th century, it grew into a railroad suburb.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p01] Faster transportation enabled rapid population growth in the late 19th century, involving the move from horse-drawn street cars to elevated railways and the subway system, which linked to Manhattan in 1904.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p01] The South Bronx was a manufacturing center for many years, and was noted as a center of piano manufacturing in the early part of the 20th century.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p01] In 1919, the Bronx was the site of 63 piano factories employing more than 5,000 workers.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p01] Before the end of World War I, the Bronx hosted the rather small 1918 World's Fair at 177th Street and DeVoe Avenue.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p01] The Bronx underwent rapid urban growth after World War I.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p01] Extensions of the New York City Subway contributed to the increase in population as thousands of immigrants came to the Bronx, resulting in a major boom in residential construction.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p01] Among these groups, many Irish Americans, Italian Americans, and especially Jewish Americans settled here.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p01] French, German, Polish, and other immigrants moved into the borough.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p01] As evidence of the change in population, by 1937, 592,185 Jews lived in the Bronx (43.9% of the borough's population), while only 54,000 Jews lived in the borough in 2011.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p01] Many synagogues still stand in the Bronx, but most have been converted to other uses.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p01] Bootleggers and gangs were active in the Bronx during Prohibition, between 1920 and 1933.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p01] Irish, Italian, Jewish, and Polish gangs smuggled in most of the illegal whiskey, and the oldest sections of the borough became poverty-stricken.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p01] Police Commissioner Richard Enright said that speakeasies provided a place for "the vicious elements, bootleggers, gamblers and their friends in all walks of life" to cooperate and to "evade the law, escape punishment for their crimes, [and] to deter the police from doing their duty".
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p01] In 1945, the Bronx Marian apparitions drew 30,000 pilgrims to the area to see the site of an alleged vision of the Virgin Mary.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p01] Between 1930 and 1960, moderate and upper income Bronxites, predominantly non-Hispanic Whites, began to relocate from the borough's southwestern neighborhoods.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p01] This migration has left a mostly poor African American and Hispanic, largely Puerto Rican, population in the West Bronx.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p01] A significant factor that shifted the racial and economic demographics was the construction of Co-op City, built to house middle-class residents in family-sized apartments.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p01] The high-rise complex played a significant role in draining middle-class residents from older tenement buildings in the borough's southern and western fringes.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p01] Most predominantly non-Hispanic White communities today are in the eastern and northwestern sections of the borough.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p01] From the mid-1960s to the early 1980s, the quality of life changed for some Bronx residents.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p01] Historians and social scientists have suggested many factors, including the theory that Robert Moses' Cross Bronx Expressway destroyed existing residential neighborhoods and created instant slums, as put forward in Robert Caro's biography *The Power Broker*.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p01] Another factor in the Bronx's decline may have been the development of high-rise housing projects, particularly in the South Bronx.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p01] Yet another factor may have been a reduction in the real estate listings and property-related financial services offered in some areas of the Bronx, such as mortgage loans or insurance policies—a process known as redlining.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p01] Others have suggested a "planned shrinkage" of municipal services, such as fire-fighting.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p01] There was also much debate as to whether rent control laws had made it less profitable (or more costly) for landlords to maintain existing buildings with their existing tenants than to abandon or destroy those buildings.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p01] In the 1970s, parts of the Bronx were plagued by a wave of arson.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p01] The burning of buildings was predominantly in the poorest communities, such as the South Bronx.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p01] One explanation of this event was that landlords decided to burn their low property-value buildings and take the insurance money, as it was easier for them to get insurance money than to try to refurbish a dilapidated building or sell a building in a severely distressed area.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p01] The Bronx became identified with a high rate of poverty and unemployment, which was mainly a persistent problem in the South Bronx.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p01] There were cases where tenants set fire to the building they lived in so they could qualify for emergency relocations by city social service agencies to better residences, sometimes being relocated to other parts of the city.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p01] Out of 289 census tracts in the Bronx borough, 7 tracts lost more than 97% of their buildings to arson and abandonment between 1970 and 1980; another 44 tracts had more than 50% of their buildings meet the same fate.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p01] By the early 1980s, the Bronx was considered the most blighted urban area in the country, particularly the South Bronx which experienced a loss of 60% of the population and 40% of housing units.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p01] However, starting in the 1990s, many of the burned-out and run-down tenements were replaced by new housing units.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p01] In May 1984, New York Supreme Court justice Peter J.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p01] Since the late 1980s, significant development has occurred in the Bronx, first stimulated by the city's "Ten-Year Housing Plan" and community members working to rebuild the social, economic and environmental infrastructure by creating affordable housing.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p01] Groups affiliated with churches in the South Bronx erected the Nehemiah Homes with about 1,000 units.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p01] The grass roots organization Nos Quedamos' endeavor known as Melrose Commons began to rebuild areas in the South Bronx.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p01] The IRT White Plains Road Line (2 and 5 trains) began to show an increase in riders.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p01] Chains such as Marshalls, Staples, and Target opened stores in the Bronx.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p01] More bank branches opened in the Bronx as a whole (rising from 106 in 1997 to 149 in 2007), although not primarily in poor or minority neighborhoods, while the Bronx still has fewer branches per person than other boroughs.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p01] In 1997, the Bronx was designated an *All America City* by the National Civic League, acknowledging its comeback from the decline of the mid-century.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p01] Between 2002 and June 2007, 33,687 new units of housing were built or were under way and $4.8 billion has been invested in new housing.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p01] In the first six months of 2007 alone total investment in new residential development was $965 million and 5,187 residential units were scheduled to be completed.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p01] Much of the new development is springing up in formerly vacant lots across the South Bronx.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p01] In addition there came a revitalization of the existing housing market in areas such as Hunts Point, the Lower Concourse, and the neighborhoods surrounding the Third Avenue Bridge as people buy apartments and renovate them.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p01] Several boutique and chain hotels opened in the 2010s in the South Bronx.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p01] The Bronx General Post Office on the corner of the Grand Concourse and East 149th Street is being converted into a market place, boutiques, restaurants and office space with a USPS concession.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p01] The Kingsbridge Armory, often cited as the largest armory in the world, is currently slated for redevelopment.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p01] Under consideration for future development is the construction of a platform over the New York City Subway's Concourse Yard adjacent to Lehman College.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p01] The construction permitted approximately 2,000,000 square feet (190,000 m2) of development and cost US$350–500 million.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p01] Despite significant investment compared to the post war period, many exacerbated social problems remain including high rates of violent crime, substance abuse, overcrowding, and substandard housing conditions.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p01] The Bronx has the highest rate of poverty in New York City, and the greater South Bronx is the poorest area.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p01] Census Bureau, Bronx County has a total area of 57 square miles (150 km2), of which 42 square miles (110 km2) is land and 15 square miles (39 km2) (27%) is water.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p01] The Bronx is New York City's northernmost borough, New York State's southernmost mainland county and the only part of New York City that is almost entirely on the North American mainland, unlike the other four boroughs that are either islands or located on islands.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p01] The bedrock of the West Bronx is primarily *Fordham gneiss*, a high-grade heavily banded metamorphic rock containing significant amounts of pink feldspar.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p01] Marble Hill – politically part of Manhattan but now physically attached to the Bronx – is so-called because of the formation of Inwood marble there as well as in Inwood, Manhattan, and parts of the Bronx and Westchester County.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p01] The Hudson River separates the Bronx on the west from Alpine, Tenafly and Englewood Cliffs in Bergen County, New Jersey.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p01] The Harlem River separates it from the island of Manhattan to the southwest.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p01] The East River separates it from Queens to the southeast.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p01] To the east, Long Island Sound separates it from Nassau County in western Long Island.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p01] Directly north of the Bronx are (from west to east) the adjoining Westchester County communities of Yonkers, Mount Vernon, Pelham Manor and New Rochelle.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p01] There is also a short southern land boundary with Marble Hill in the Borough of Manhattan, over the filled-in former course of the Spuyten Duyvil Creek; Marble Hill's postal ZIP code, telephonic area codes and fire service, however, are shared with the Bronx and not Manhattan.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p01] The Bronx River flows south from Westchester County through the borough, emptying into the East River; it is the only entirely freshwater river in New York City.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p01] It separates the West Bronx from the schist of the East Bronx.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p01] A smaller river, the Hutchinson River (named after the religious leader Anne Hutchinson, killed along its banks in 1641), passes through the East Bronx and empties into Eastchester Bay.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p01] The Bronx includes several small islands in the East River and Long Island Sound, such as City Island and Hart Island.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p01] Rikers Island in the East River, home to the large jail complex for the entire city, is also part of the Bronx.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p01] The Bronx's highest elevation at 280 feet (85 m) is in the northwest corner, west of Van Cortlandt Park and in the Chapel Farm area near the Riverdale Country School.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p01] The opposite (southeastern) side of the Bronx has four large low peninsulas or "necks" of low-lying land that jut into the waters of the East River and were once salt marsh: Hunt's Point, Clason's Point, Screvin's Neck and Throggs Neck.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p01] Further up the coastline, Rodman's Neck lies between Pelham Bay Park in the northeast and City Island.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p01] The Bronx's irregular shoreline extends for 75 square miles (194 km2).
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p01] Although Bronx County was the third most densely populated county in the United States in 2022 (after Manhattan and Brooklyn), 7,000 acres (28 km2) of the Bronx—about one fifth of the Bronx's area, and one quarter of its land area—is given over to parkland.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p01] The vision of a system of major Bronx parks connected by park-like thoroughfares is usually attributed to John Mullaly.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p01] Woodlawn Cemetery, located on 400 acres (160 ha) and one of the largest cemeteries in New York City, sits on the western bank of the Bronx River near Yonkers.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p01] It opened in 1863, in what was then the town of Yonkers, at the time a rural area.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p01] Since the first burial in 1865, more than 300,000 people have been interred there.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p01] The borough's northern side includes the largest park in New York City—Pelham Bay Park, which includes Orchard Beach—and the third-largest, Van Cortlandt Park, which is west of Woodlawn Cemetery and borders Yonkers.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p01] Also in the northern Bronx, Wave Hill, the former estate of George W.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p01] Perkins—known for a historic house, gardens, changing site-specific art installations and concerts—overlooks the New Jersey Palisades from a promontory on the Hudson in Riverdale.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p01] Nearer the borough's center, and along the Bronx River, is Bronx Park.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p01] Its northern end houses the New York Botanical Gardens, which preserve the last patch of the original hemlock forest that once covered the county, and its southern end the Bronx Zoo, the largest urban zoological gardens in the United States.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p01] In 1904, the Chestnut Blight pathogen (*Cryphonectria parasitica*) was found for the first time outside of Asia, at the Bronx Zoo.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p01] Over the next 40 years it spread throughout eastern North America and killed back essentially every American Chestnut (*Castanea dentata*), causing ecological and economic devastation.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p01] Just south of Van Cortlandt Park is the Jerome Park Reservoir, surrounded by 2 miles (3 km) of stone walls and bordering several small parks in the Bedford Park neighborhood; the reservoir was built in the 1890s on the site of the former Jerome Park Racetrack.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p01] Further south is Crotona Park, home to a 3.3-acre (1.3 ha) lake, 28 species of trees, and a large swimming pool.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p01] The land for these parks, and many others, was bought by New York City in 1888, while land was still open and inexpensive, in anticipation of future needs and future pressures for development.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p01] Some of the acquired land was set aside for the Grand Concourse and Pelham Parkway, the first of a series of boulevards and parkways, thoroughfares lined with trees, vegetation and greenery.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p01] Later projects included the Bronx River Parkway, which developed a road while restoring the riverbank and reducing pollution, Mosholu Parkway and the Henry Hudson Parkway.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p01] In 2006, a five-year, $220-million program of capital improvements and natural restoration in 70 Bronx parks was begun (financed by water and sewer revenues) as part of an agreement that allowed a water filtration plant under Mosholu Golf Course in Van Cortlandt Park.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p01] One major focus is on opening more of the Bronx River's banks and restoring them to a natural state.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p01] There are two primary systems for dividing the Bronx into regions, which do not necessarily agree with one another.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p01] One system is based on the Bronx River, while the other strictly separates South Bronx from the rest of the borough.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p01] The Bronx River divides the borough nearly in half, putting the earlier-settled, more urban, and hillier sections in the west and the newer, more suburban coastal sections in the east.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p01] It is an accurate reflection on the Bronx's history considering that the towns that existed in the area prior to annexation to the City of New York generally did not straddle the Bronx River.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p01] In addition, what is today the Bronx was annexed to New York City in two stages: areas west of the Bronx River were annexed in 1874, while areas to the east of the river were annexed in 1895.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p01] The number, locations, and boundaries of the Bronx's neighborhoods (many of them sitting on the sites of 19th-century villages) have become unclear with time and successive waves of newcomers.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p01] Even city officials do not necessarily agree.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p01] Major neighborhoods of the Bronx include the following.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p01] East of the Bronx River, the borough is relatively flat and includes four large low peninsulas, or 'necks,' of low-lying land which jut into the waters of the East River and were once saltmarsh: Hunts Point, Clason's Point, Screvin's Neck (Castle Hill Point) and Throgs Neck.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p01] The East Bronx has older tenement buildings, low income public housing complexes, and multifamily homes, as well as single family homes.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p01] It includes New York City's largest park: Pelham Bay Park along the Westchester-Bronx border.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p01] City Island is east of Pelham Bay Park in Long Island Sound and is known for its seafood restaurants and private waterfront homes.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p01] City Island's single shopping street, City Island Avenue, is reminiscent of a small New England town.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p01] It is connected to Rodman's Neck on the mainland by the City Island Bridge.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p01] East of City Island is Hart Island, which is uninhabited and not open to the public.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p01] It once served as a prison and now houses New York City's potter's field for unclaimed bodies.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p01] The western parts of the Bronx are hillier and are dominated by a series of parallel ridges, running south to north.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p01] The West Bronx has older apartment buildings, low income public housing complexes, multifamily homes in its lower income areas as well as larger single family homes in more affluent areas such as Riverdale and Fieldston.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p01] It includes New York City's third-largest park: Van Cortlandt Park along the Westchester-Bronx border.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p01] The Grand Concourse, a wide boulevard, runs through it, north to south.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p01] Neighborhoods include: Fordham-Bedford, Bedford Park, Norwood, Kingsbridge Heights *(Community District 7)*, Kingsbridge, Riverdale *(Community District 8)*, and Woodlawn Heights *(Community District 12)*.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p01] Like other neighborhoods in New York City, the South Bronx has no official boundaries.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p01] The name has been used to represent poverty in the Bronx and is applied to progressively more northern places so that by the 2000s, Fordham Road was often used as a northern limit.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p01] The Bronx River more consistently forms an eastern boundary.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p01] The South Bronx has many high-density apartment buildings, low income public housing complexes, and multi-unit homes.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p01] The South Bronx is home to the Bronx County Courthouse, Borough Hall, and other government buildings, as well as Yankee Stadium.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p01] The Cross Bronx Expressway bisects it, east to west.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p01] The South Bronx has some of the poorest neighborhoods in the country, as well as very high crime areas.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p01] *(Community District 5 & Community District 7)*.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p01] The borough's most populous racial group, White, declined from 99.3% in 1920 to 14.9% in 2018.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p01] The Bronx has 532,487 housing units, with a median value of $371,800, and with an owner-occupancy rate of 19.7%, the lowest of the five boroughs.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p01] There are 495,356 households, with 2.85 persons per household.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p01] 59.3% of residents speak a language besides English at home, the highest rate of the five boroughs.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p01] The per capita income is $19,721, while the median household income is $36,593, both being the lowest of the five boroughs.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p01] 27.9% of residents live below the poverty line, the highest of the five boroughs.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p01] In total, 55.98% (706,783) of the Bronx's population age five and older spoke a language at home other than English.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p01] A Garifuna-speaking community from Honduras and Guatemala also makes the Bronx its home.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p01] The Bronx is the only New York City borough with a Hispanic majority, many of whom are Puerto Ricans and Dominicans.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p01] According to the 2009 American Community Survey, Black Americans were the second largest racial/ethnic group in the Bronx.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p01] Black people of both Hispanic and non-Hispanic origin represented over one-third (35.4%) of the Bronx's population.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p01] Black people of non-Hispanic origin made up 30.8% of the population.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p01] Over 495,200 Black people resided in the borough, of whom 87% were non-Hispanic.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p01] Over 61,000 people identified themselves as Sub-Saharan African in the survey, making up 4.4% of the population.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p01] Multiracial Americans are also a sizable minority in the Bronx.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p01] People of multiracial heritage number over 41,800 individuals and represent 3.0% of the population.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p01] People of mixed African American and European American heritage number over 6,850 members and form 0.5% of the population.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p01] People of mixed Native American and European heritage number over 2,450 members and form 0.2% of the population.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p01] People of mixed Asian and European heritage number over 880 members and form 0.1% of the population.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p01] People of mixed African American and Native American heritage number over 1,220 members and form 0.1% of the population.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p01] Out of all five boroughs, the Bronx has the lowest number and proportion of white residents.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p01] As of 2009, White Americans of both Hispanic and non-Hispanic origin represented over one-fifth (22.9%) of the Bronx's population, or 320,640 people.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p01] Non-Hispanic White people accounted for one-eighth of the population (12.1%, or 168,570 12.1%).
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p01] This is in contrast to a century ago, when almost all Bronx residents were white (99.3% in 1920).
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p01] That share fell to about one-third by 1980 (34.4%).
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p01] As of 2009, White Americans of both Hispanic and non-Hispanic origin represented one-fifth (22.9%) of the Bronx's population, but counting non-Hispanic White people the proportion was under one-eighth (12.1%).
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p01] The majority of the non-Hispanic European American population is of Italian and Irish descent.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p01] People of Italian descent numbered over 55,000 individuals and made up 3.9% of the population.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p01] People of Irish descent numbered over 43,500 individuals and made up 3.1% of the population.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p01] German Americans and Polish Americans made up 1.4% and 0.8% of the population respectively.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p01] The Bronx has the largest Albanian community in the United States.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p01] As of 2018, non-Hispanic White people account for about one in seven residents (14.9% in 2018).
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p01] The census of 1930 counted only 1.0% (12,930) of the Bronx's population as Negro (while making no distinct counts of Hispanic or Spanish-surname residents).
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p01] As of the 2010 census, there were 1,385,108 people living in the Bronx, a 3.9% increase since 2000.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p01] As of the 2000 United States census, there were 1,332,650 people, 463,212 households, and 314,984 families residing in the borough.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p01] The population density was 31,709.3 inhabitants per square mile (12,243.0 inhabitants/km2).
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p01] There were 490,659 housing units at an average density of 11,674.8 units per square mile (4,507.7 units/km2).
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p01] Census estimates place total population of Bronx county at 1,392,002 as of 2012.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p01] There were 463,212 households, out of which 38.1% had children under the age of 18 living with them, 31.4% were married couples living together, 30.4% had a female householder with no husband present, and 32.0% were non-families.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p01] 27.4% of all households were made up of individuals, and 9.4% had someone living alone who was 65 years of age or older.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p01] The average household size was 2.78 and the average family size was 3.37.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p01] The age distribution of the population in the Bronx were as follows: 29.8% under the age of 18, 10.6% from 18 to 24, 30.7% from 25 to 44, 18.8% from 45 to 64, and 10.1% 65 years of age or older.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p01] For every 100 females, there were 87.0 males.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p01] The 1999 median income for a household in the borough was $27,611, and the median family income was $30,682.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p01] Men had a median income of $31,178 versus $29,429 for women.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p01] The per capita income for the borough was $13,959.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p01] About 28.0% of families and 30.7% of the population were below the poverty line, including 41.5% of those under age 18 and 21.3% of those age 65 or over.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p01] More than half of the neighborhoods in the Bronx are high poverty or extreme poverty areas.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p01] From 2015 census data, the median income for a household was (in 2015 dollars) $34,299.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p01] Per capita income in past 12 months (in 2015 dollars): $18,456 with persons in poverty at 30.3%.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p01] Per the 2016 Census data, the median income for a household was $35,302.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p02] The Bronx is the home of the New York Yankees—nicknamed "the Bronx Bombers"—of Major League Baseball.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p02] The Yankees have won 27 World Series titles, more than any other team, and their roster has featured players like Babe Ruth, Lou Gehrig, Joe DiMaggio, and Mickey Mantle.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p02] When the team's original Yankee Stadium opened in 1923, it was the largest baseball park.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p02] The field also hosted college football games, and was the home of two National Football League teams, the New York Yankees (1926–1929) and the New York Giants (1956–1973).
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p02] In 2008, the park was replaced with the current Yankee Stadium.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p02] The Bronx additionally hosts the only Major League Soccer team in the five boroughs, the New York City FC, which also plays in Yankee Stadium.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p02] Part of the New York City Marathon travels through the Bronx, including the notoriously difficult Mile 20.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p02] From 1889 to 1904, the borough used to have a horse racing facility, the Morris Park Racecourse.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p02] In its later years, the course was used for motor racing: a new land speed record was reached on the track.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p02] College teams in the Bronx include the Fordham Rams and the Lehman Lightning.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p02] The Bronx has had a long association with music.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p02] In the early 20th century, it was a center for the evolution of Latin jazz.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p02] The Bronx Opera was established in 1967.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p02] In the 1970s, the Bronx was strongly associated with the development of hip-hop, which evolved during a decade of demographic and economic decline for the borough.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p02] One of the genre's pioneers, DJ Kool Herc, held parties in the community room of an apartment building at 1520 Sedgwick Avenue, where he experimented with turntablist techniques such as mixing and scratching of funk records, as well as rapping during extended instrumentals.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p02] Other significant Bronx DJs from this period include Grandmaster Flash and Afrika Bambaataa.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p02] In addition, the Bronx was an important base for drill culture, with the rise of rappers such as Kay Flock, Sha EK and many others.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p02] The Bronx is home to several Off-Off-Broadway theaters, many staging new works by immigrant playwrights from Latin America and Africa.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p02] The Pregones Theater, which produces Latin American work, opened a new 130-seat theater in 2005 on Walton Avenue in the South Bronx.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p02] Some artists from elsewhere in New York City have begun to converge on the area, and housing prices have nearly quadrupled in the area since 2002.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p02] However, rising prices directly correlate to a housing shortage across the city and the entire metro area.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p02] The Bronx Academy of Arts and Dance, founded in 1998 by Arthur Aviles and Charles Rice-González, provides dance, theatre and art workshops, festivals and performances focusing on contemporary and modern art in relation to race, gender and sexuality.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p02] It is home to the Arthur Aviles Typical Theatre, a contemporary dance company, and the Bronx Dance Coalition.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p02] The academy was formerly in the American Bank Note Company Building before relocating to a venue on the grounds of St.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p02] The Bronx Museum of the Arts, founded in 1971, exhibits 20th century and contemporary art through its central museum space and 11,000 square feet (1,000 m2) of galleries.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p02] Many of its exhibitions are on themes of special interest to the Bronx.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p02] Its permanent collection features more than 800 works of art, primarily by artists from Africa, Asia and Latin America, including paintings, photographs, prints, drawings, and mixed media.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p02] The museum was temporarily closed in 2006 while it underwent an expansion designed by the architectural firm Arquitectonica that would double the museum's size to 33,000 square feet (3,100 m2).
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p02] The Bronx has also become home to a peculiar poetic tribute in the form of the "Heinrich Heine Memorial", better known as the Lorelei Fountain.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p02] However, this intention was thwarted by a combination of ethnic antagonism, aesthetic controversy and political struggles over the institutional control of public art.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p02] In 1899, the memorial by Ernst Gustav Herter was placed in Joyce Kilmer Park, near the Yankee Stadium.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p02] In 1999, it was moved to 161st Street and the Concourse.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p02] The peninsular borough's maritime heritage is acknowledged in several ways.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p02] The City Island Historical Society and Nautical Museum occupies a former public school designed by the New York City school system's turn-of-the-last-century master architect C.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p02] The state's Maritime College in Fort Schuyler (on the southeastern shore) houses the Maritime Industry Museum.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p02] In addition, the Harlem River is reemerging as "Scullers' Row" due in large part to the efforts of the Bronx River Restoration Project, a joint public-private endeavor of the city's parks department.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p02] Canoeing and kayaking on the borough's namesake river have been promoted by the Bronx River Alliance.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p02] The river is also straddled by the New York Botanical Gardens, its neighbor, the Bronx Zoo, and a little further south, on the west shore, Bronx River Art Center.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p02] "Bronx Week", traditionally held in May, began as a one-day celebration.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p02] Begun by Bronx historian Lloyd Ultan and supported by then borough president Robert Abrams, the original one-day program was based on the "Bronx Borough Day" festival which took place in the 1920s.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p02] The following year, at the height of the decade's civil unrest, the festival was extended to a one-week event.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p02] In the 1980s the key event, the "Bronx Ball", was launched.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p02] The week includes the Bronx Week Parade as well as inductions into the "Bronx Walk of Fame".
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p02] Various Bronx neighborhoods conduct their own community celebrations.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p02] The Arthur Avenue "Little Italy" neighborhood conducts an annual Autumn Ferragosto Festival that celebrates Italian culture.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p02] Hunts Point hosts an annual "Fish Parade and Summer Festival" at the start of summer.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p02] Edgewater Park hosts an annual "Ragamuffin" children's walk in November.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p02] There are several events to honor the borough's veterans.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p02] Albanian Independence Day is also observed.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p02] There are also parades to celebrate Dominican, Italian, and Irish heritage.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p02] The Bronx is home to several local newspapers and radio and television studios.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p02] The Bronx has several local newspapers, including The Bronx Daily, *The Bronx News*, *Parkchester News*, *City News*, *The Norwood News*, *The Riverdale Press*, *Riverdale Review*, *The Bronx Times Reporter*, and *Co-op City Times*.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p02] Four non-profit news outlets, *Norwood News*, *Mount Hope Monitor*, *Mott Haven Herald* and *The Hunts Point Express* serve the borough's poorer communities.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p02] The editor and co-publisher of *The Riverdale Press*, Bernard Stein, won the Pulitzer Prize for Editorial Writing for his editorials about Bronx and New York City issues in 1998.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p02] The Bronx once had its own daily newspaper, *The Bronx Home News*, which started publishing on January 20, 1907, and merged into the *New York Post* in 1948.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p02] It became a special section of the *Post*, sold only in the Bronx, and eventually disappeared from view.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p02] One of New York City's major non-commercial radio broadcasters is WFUV, a National Public Radio-affiliated 50,000-watt station broadcasting from Fordham University's Rose Hill campus in the Bronx.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p02] The radio station's antenna was relocated to the top of an apartment building owned by Montefiore Medical Center, which expanded the reach of the station's signal.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p02] The City of New York has an official television station run by NYC Media and broadcasting from Bronx Community College, and Cablevision operates News 12 The Bronx, both of which feature programming based in the Bronx.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p02] Co-op City was the first area in the Bronx, and the first in New York beyond Manhattan, to have its own cable television provider.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p02] The local public-access television station BronxNet originates from Herbert H.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p02] Lehman College, the borough's only four year CUNY school, and provides government-access television (GATV) public affairs programming in addition to programming produced by Bronx residents.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p02] Prominent shopping areas in the Bronx include Fordham Road, Bay Plaza in Co-op City, The Hub, the Riverdale/Kingsbridge shopping center, and Bruckner Boulevard.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p02] Shops are also concentrated on streets aligned underneath elevated railroad lines, including Westchester Avenue, White Plains Road, Jerome Avenue, Southern Boulevard, and Broadway.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p02] The Bronx Terminal Market contains several big-box stores, which opened in 2009 south of Yankee Stadium.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p02] The Bronx has three primary shopping centers: The Hub, Gateway Center and Southern Boulevard.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p02] The Hub–Third Avenue Business Improvement District (B.I.D.), in The Hub, is the retail heart of the South Bronx, where four roads converge: East 149th Street, Willis, Melrose and Third Avenues.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p02] It is primarily inside the neighborhood of Melrose but also lines the northern border of Mott Haven.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p02] The Hub has been called "the Broadway of the Bronx", being likened to the real Broadway in Manhattan and the northwestern Bronx.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p02] It is the site of both maximum traffic and architectural density.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p02] In configuration, it resembles a miniature Times Square, a spatial "bow-tie" created by the geometry of the street.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p02] The Hub is part of Bronx Community Board 1.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p02] The $500 million shopping center, which was completed in 2009, saw the construction of new buildings and two smaller buildings, one new and the other a renovation of an existing building that was part of the original market.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p02] The two main buildings are linked by a six-level garage for 2,600 cars.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p02] The center's design has earned it a LEED "Silver" designation.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p02] Since New York City's consolidation in 1898, the New York City Charter that provides for a "strong" mayor–council system has governed the Bronx.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p02] The centralized New York City government is responsible for public education, correctional institutions, libraries, public safety, recreational facilities, sanitation, water supply, and welfare services in the Bronx.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p02] The office of Borough President was created in the consolidation of 1898 to balance centralization with local authority.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p02] Each borough president had a powerful administrative role derived from having a vote on the New York City Board of Estimate, which was responsible for creating and approving the city's budget and proposals for land use.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p02] Since 1990, the Borough President has acted as an advocate for the borough at the mayoral agencies, the City Council, the New York state government, and corporations.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p02] Until March 1, 2009, the Borough President of the Bronx was Adolfo Carrión Jr., elected as a Democrat in 2001 and 2005 before retiring early to direct the White House Office of Urban Affairs Policy.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p02] In 2021, Rubén Díaz's Democratic successor, Vanessa Gibson was elected (began serving in 2022) with 79.9% of the vote against 13.4% for Janell King (Republican) and 6.5% for Sammy Ravelo (Conservative).
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p02] All of the Bronx's currently elected public officials have first won the nomination of the Democratic Party (in addition to any other endorsements).
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p02] Local party platforms center on affordable housing, education and economic development.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p02] Controversial political issues in the Bronx include environmental issues, the cost of housing, and annexation of parkland for new Yankee Stadium.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p02] Since its separation from New York County on January 1, 1914, the Bronx, has had, like each of the other 61 counties of New York State, its own criminal court system and District Attorney, the chief public prosecutor who is directly elected by popular vote.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p02] Clark has been the Bronx County District Attorney since 2016.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p02] Johnson, the District Attorney from 1989 to 2015.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p02] He was the first African-American District Attorney in New York State.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p02] The Bronx also has twelve Community Boards, appointed bodies that advise on land use and municipal facilities and services for local residents, businesses and institutions.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p02] After becoming a separate county in 1914, the Bronx has supported only two Republican presidential candidates.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p02] It voted heavily for the winning Republican Warren G.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p02] Harding in 1920, but much more narrowly on a split vote for his victorious Republican successor Calvin Coolidge in 1924 (Coolidge 79,562; John W.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p02] Davis, Dem., 72,834; Robert La Follette, 62,202 equally divided between the Progressive and Socialist lines).
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p02] Since then, the Bronx has always supported the Democratic Party's nominee for president, starting with a vote of 2–1 for the unsuccessful Al Smith in 1928, followed by four 2–1 votes for the successful Franklin D.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p02] (Both had been Governors of New York, but Republican former Gov.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p02] Dewey won only 28% of the Bronx's vote in 1948 against 55% for Pres.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p02] Harry Truman, the winning Democrat, and 17% for Henry A.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p02] The Bronx has often shown striking differences from other boroughs in elections for Mayor.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p02] The only Republican to carry the Bronx since 1914 was Fiorello La Guardia in 1933, 1937, and 1941 (and in the latter two elections, only because his 30% to 32% vote on the American Labor Party line was added to 22% to 23% as a Republican).
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p02] The Bronx was thus the only borough not carried by the successful Republican re-election campaigns of Mayors Rudy Giuliani in 1997 and Michael Bloomberg in 2005.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p02] In every subsequent election through 1933, the Bronx gave the Socialist Party candidate a higher percent of the vote than any other borough.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p02] Education in the Bronx is provided by a large number of public and private institutions, many of which draw students who live beyond the Bronx.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p02] The New York City Department of Education manages the borough's public noncharter schools.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p02] In 2000, public schools enrolled nearly 280,000 of the Bronx's residents over three years old (out of 333,100 enrolled in all pre-college schools).
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p02] There are also several public charter schools.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p02] Private schools range from elite independent schools to religiously affiliated schools run by the Roman Catholic Archdiocese of New York and Jewish organizations.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p02] This arrangement has been in place since 1948.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p02] In 2000, according to the United States census, out of the nearly 800,000 people in the Bronx who were then at least 25 years old, 62.3% had graduated from high school and 14.6% held a bachelor's or higher college degree.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p02] These percentages were lower than those for New York's other boroughs, which ranged from 68.8% (Brooklyn) to 82.6% (Staten Island) for high school graduates over 24, and from 21.8% (Brooklyn) to 49.4% (Manhattan) for college graduates.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p02] In the 2000 Census, 79,240 of the nearly 95,000 Bronx residents enrolled in high school attended public schools.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p02] Lehman High School and High School of American Studies.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p02] The Bronx is also home to three of New York City's most prestigious private, secular schools: Fieldston, Horace Mann, and Riverdale Country School.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p02] High schools linked to the Catholic Church include: St.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p02] Raymond Academy for Girls, All Hallows High School, Fordham Preparatory School, Monsignor Scanlan High School, St.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p02] Raymond High School for Boys, Cardinal Hayes High School, Cardinal Spellman High School, The Academy of Mount Saint Ursula, Aquinas High School, Preston High School, St.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p02] Catharine Academy, Mount Saint Michael Academy, and St.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p02] The SAR Academy and SAR High School are Modern Orthodox Jewish Yeshiva coeducational day schools in Riverdale, with roots in Manhattan's Lower East Side.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p02] In the 1990s, New York City began closing the large, public high schools in the Bronx and replacing them with small high schools.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p02] Among the reasons cited for the changes were poor graduation rates and concerns about safety.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p02] Schools that have been closed or reduced in size include John F.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p02] Kennedy, James Monroe, Taft, Theodore Roosevelt, Adlai Stevenson, Evander Childs, Christopher Columbus, Morris, Walton, and South Bronx High Schools.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p02] In 2000, 49,442 (57.5%) of the 86,014 Bronx residents seeking college, graduate or professional degrees attended public institutions.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p02] Several colleges and universities are in the Bronx.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p02] John's College in 1841 by the Diocese of New York as the first Catholic institution of higher education in the northeast.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p02] It is now officially an independent institution, but strongly embraces its Jesuit heritage.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p02] The 85-acre (340,000 m2) Bronx campus, known as Rose Hill, is the main campus of the university, and is among the largest within the city (other Fordham campuses are in Manhattan and Westchester County).
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p02] Three campuses of the City University of New York are in the Bronx: Hostos Community College, Bronx Community College (occupying the former University Heights Campus of New York University) and Herbert H.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p02] Lehman College (formerly the uptown campus of Hunter College), which offers both undergraduate and graduate degrees.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p02] The College of Mount Saint Vincent is a Catholic liberal arts college in Riverdale under the direction of the Sisters of Charity of New York.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p02] Founded in 1847 as a school for girls, the academy became a degree-granting college in 1911 and began admitting men in 1974.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p02] Its campus is also home to the Academy for Jewish Religion, a transdenominational rabbinical and cantorial school.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p02] Manhattan University is a Catholic college in Riverdale which offers undergraduate programs in the arts, business, education, engineering, and science.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p02] It also offers graduate programs in education and engineering.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p02] Albert Einstein College of Medicine, part of the Montefiore Medical Center, is in Morris Park.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p02] The coeducational and non-sectarian Mercy University—with its main campus in Dobbs Ferry—has a Bronx campus near Westchester Square.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p02] The State University of New York Maritime College in Fort Schuyler (Throggs Neck)—at the far southeastern tip of the Bronx—is the national leader in maritime education and houses the Maritime Industry Museum.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p02] In addition, the private, proprietary Monroe University, focused on preparation for business and the professions, started in the Bronx in 1933 and now has a campus in New Rochelle (Westchester County) as well the Bronx's Fordham neighborhood.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p02] Like the northernmost part of upper Manhattan, the West Bronx's hilly terrain leaves a relatively free-style street grid.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p02] Much of the West Bronx's street numbering carries over from upper Manhattan, but does not match it exactly; East 132nd Street is the lowest numbered street in the Bronx.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p02] This dates from the mid-19th century when the southwestern area of Westchester County west of the Bronx River, was incorporated into New York City and known as the Northside.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p02] The East Bronx is considerably flatter, and the street layout tends to be more regular.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p02] Only the Wakefield neighborhood picks up the street numbering, albeit at a misalignment due to Tremont Avenue's layout.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p02] At the same diagonal latitude, West 262nd Street in Riverdale matches East 237th Street in Wakefield.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p02] Three major north–south thoroughfares run between Manhattan and the Bronx: Third Avenue, Park Avenue, and Broadway.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p02] Other major north–south roads include the Grand Concourse, Jerome Avenue, Sedgwick Avenue, Webster Avenue, and White Plains Road.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p02] Major east-west thoroughfares include Mosholu Parkway, Gun Hill Road, Fordham Road, Pelham Parkway, and Tremont Avenue.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p02] Most east–west streets are prefixed with either *East* or *West*, to indicate on which side of Jerome Avenue they lie (continuing the similar system in Manhattan, which uses Fifth Avenue as the dividing line).
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p02] The historic Boston Post Road, part of the long pre-revolutionary road connecting Boston with other northeastern cities, runs east–west in some places, and sometimes northeast–southwest.
[src:esther-lederberg/bronx-new-york-p02] Mosholu and Pelham Parkways, with Bronx Park between them, Van Cortlandt Park to the west and Pelham Bay Park to the east, are also linked by bridle paths.
